# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2018-freiburg-gang-rape
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] On 13 October 2018, an 18-year-old woman was raped outside a discotheque in Freiburg, Germany by a series of men.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] In July 2020, eight perpetrators were convicted of rape, while two additional men were convicted for not aiding the victim.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The case drew public attention, due in part to the refugee status of most of the perpetrators.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The woman filed a complaint with the police the next day.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] Eight suspects were soon taken into custody.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] Several suspects were identified from DNA traces found on the victim; further evaluation of traces from the victim and the scene was carried out.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The police sought more suspects, using a 13-person investigation team.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] One witness claimed that up to 15 men had raped the woman.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] Eight men were initially arrested for the crime, seven Syrians and one with German nationality.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] Three of the arrested had presented themselves on the Internet bearing firearms.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The main suspect was already targeted by an undercover investigation for violent crime and drug trafficking, and he was a suspect in another rape case.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] Police had planned to arrest him on 24 October.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] DNA traces indicated there were two further unidentified suspects who were not among the arrested.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] A ninth suspect, an 18-year-old man from Syria, was detained on 29 November in a refugee center in Freiburg, after traces of his DNA were found on the victim's clothing.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] He was in the discotheque on the night of the crime; police took a saliva sample from him.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The ninth suspect had come to Germany via the politically debated family reunification provision.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] Police continued to search for a tenth suspect whose DNA was also found on the victim.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The trial of eleven suspects began on 26 June 2019 at the *Landgericht Freiburg*.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] On July 23, 2020, a German regional court convicted ten of the eleven suspects charged in the crime.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The longest sentence was five and a half years, with the others given three to four years, and two who were convicted of not having assisted the victim were given suspended sentences.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] Martin Horn, the mayor of Freiburg, stated: "There is no tolerance for despicable acts".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] He promised to bring the perpetrators to justice swiftly.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] Thomas Strobl (CDU), the Interior Minister of Baden-Württemberg said: "If the allegations prove true, we have to deal with a vile act that leaves no one cold." Officials called for calm, stating that "It is an act by individuals, which should not be generalized".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] On Monday 29 October, a protest organised by the right-wing-populist party AfD/Junge Alternative was outnumbered by counter-protesters and the AfD event was re-routed as counter-protesters blocked their way.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] These tensions were similar to those in the aftermath of the murder of Maria Ladenburger by an Afghan migrant.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The protest was attended by about 500 people, and the counter-protest was attended by about 1,500 people.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] ZDF presenter Dunja Hayali demanded a "new and open debate" around the asylum and deportation laws because of the case.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] "That deportation procedures take so long that they cannot legally be implemented for 1,000 reasons and more is a situation that cannot continue", said Hayali, adding that her statement was not to be understood as xenophobic.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] Boris Palmer (Alliance 90/The Greens), Tübingen's Lord Mayor, demanded that criminal refugees have their freedom of movement severely restricted, and proposed accommodating them in small asylum centres in remote areas without a connection to public transport.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The current German laws would allow this according to Palmer ("Wohnsitzauflage", condition of fixed abode).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] CDU General Secretary Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer said that after a deportation, criminals should be refused re-entry not only to Germany but also to the whole Schengen area for life, mentioning the gang rape in Freiburg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The interior minister of Baden-Württemberg, Thomas Strobl, was called to the committee of the interior (German: *Innenausschuss*) of the Bundestag to explain why the main suspect had not been apprehended despite there being warrants for his arrest (German: *Haftbefehle*).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The two-week delay in the incident in Freiburg becoming public along with the delayed reporting of another gang rape case in Munich where asylum seekers were suspects started a debate as to whether the late reporting was deliberate.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] Criminologist Christian Pfeiffer said that such delays are not politically motivated but reflect the fact that group crimes take longer to process where a network of suspects is involved, and even longer when police are forced to use interpreters.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/2018-freiburg-gang-rape] The victim suffers a post-traumatic stress disorder lasting at least until the verdict (as of 23 July 2020).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Since November 2024, Franziska Brantner and Felix Banaszak have been co-leaders of the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It currently holds 85 of the 630 seats in the Bundestag, having won 11% of first votes and 11.6% of second votes cast in the 2025 federal election, putting it in fourth place of the seven political parties by number of seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Its parliamentary co-leaders are Britta Haßelmann and Katharina Dröge.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens have been part of the federal government twice: first as a junior partner to the Social Democrats (SPD) from 1998 to 2005, and then with the SPD and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) in the traffic light coalition from the 2021 election until that coalition's collapse in 2024.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the Scholz cabinet, the Greens had five ministers, including Vice-Chancellor Robert Habeck and Foreign Minister Annalena Baerbock.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party holds seats in most of Germany's state legislatures, except Saarland, Thuringia and Brandenburg, and is a member of coalition governments in seven states.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Cem Özdemir, Minister-President of Baden-Württemberg, is the only Green head of government in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Landtag of Baden-Württemberg is also the only state legislature in which Alliance 90/The Greens is the largest party; it is the second largest party in the legislatures of Berlin, Hamburg and Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Alliance 90/The Greens is a founding member of the European Green Party and the Greens–European Free Alliance group in the European Parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It is currently the largest party in the G/EFA group, with 21 MEPs.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 2019 European election, Alliance 90/The Greens was the second largest party in Germany, winning 20.5% of votes cast.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party had 166,000 members in February 2025, making it the third largest party in Germany by membership.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Green Party was initially founded in West Germany as *Die Grünen* (the Greens) in January 1980.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It grew out of the anti-nuclear energy, environmental, peace, new left, and new social movements of the late 20th century.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Between 1977 and 1979 local parties running on on environmental and peace issues were established across West Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Although most environmental and anti-nuclear activists were initially sceptical of these efforts, a lack of results from pressure group activity and early electoral successes meant the approach gained momentum and led to local groups amalgamating into state-level parties.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The West Berlin state branch of The Greens was founded as *Alternative Liste*, or precisely, *Alternative Liste für Demokratie und Umweltschutz* (AL; alternative list for democracy and environmental protection) in 1978 and became the official West Berlin branch of The Greens in 1980.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1993, it renamed to Alliance 90/The Greens Berlin after the merger with East Berlin's Greens and Alliance 90.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Hamburg state branch of the Green Party was called *Grün-Alternative Liste Hamburg* (GAL; green-alternative list) from its foundation in 1982 until 2012.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1984, it became the official Hamburg branch of The Greens.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In July 1978 former Christian Democrat Herbert Gruhl founded *Grüne Aktion Zukunft* (GAZ - green action future) as the beginning of a process to establish a nationwide green party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In February 1979 an electoral alliance was established to contest the first democratic elections to the European Parliament later that year under the name *Sonstige Politische Vereinigung Die Grünen* (SPV-Die Grünen - alternative political alliance, the greens).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This included GAZ, GLU, *Grüne Liste Schleswig-Holstein* and the Action Group of Independent Germans (a pro-neutrality pacifist political party which had adopted pro-environment policies in the 1970s and was predominantly present in southern Germany).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Two members of the BBU's executive, Petra Kelly and Roland Vogt, also joined the alliance, and it was also supported by prominent writer Heinrich Böll and socialist activist Rudi Dutschke.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, not all local green groups supported the coalition, including the West Berlin *Alternative Liste* and the *Bunte Liste* (Multicoloured List) in Hamburg, the latter being a rival green party to the city's GLU branch.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Both of these lists were heavily influenced by the activism of the Communist League.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] SPV-Die Grünen ran on a platform advocating a nuclear-free Europe and a Europe of the Regions, and scored 3.2 percent of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] As German electoral law provided for a generous scheme for reimbursement of election expenses, providing them to all parties scoring at least 0.5 percent of the vote, the new formation netted 4.8 million deutschmarks, after spending just 300,000 on its campaign.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This money was spent on establishing state and national party infrastructure.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] SPV-Die Grünen's success led to increased activist interest, with membership rising to around 10,000 by the end of 1979, and the Alternative and Multicoloured Lists showing more interest in joining forces with the other green groups.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A congress in October 1979 to agree a programme for the national party led to heated disagreements over economic orientation and non-violence and whether dual membership with other parties was to be permitted.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Whilst the latter was resolved by agreeing to devolve decisions on membership to local branches, the former was overcome by the adoption of what would become known as the four pillars of green politics: ecology, social responsibility, grassroots democracy and non-violence.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Journalist and activist August Haußleiter claimed to have proposed these and secured the agreement of the leaders of the right (Gruhl) and left (Jürgen Reents) factions at the conference.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The nascent movement received a further boost the same month when the *Bremer Grüne Liste* became the first green party to win seats in a state parliament, securing four seats in Bremen's election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The political party **The Greens** (German: *Die Grünen*) sprung out of the wave of New Social Movements that were active in the 1970s, including environmentalist, anti-war, and anti-nuclear movements which can trace their origin to the student protests of 1968.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Officially founded as a German national party on 13 January 1980 in Karlsruhe, the party sought to give these movements political and parliamentary representation, as the pre-existing people's parties were not organised in a way to address their stated issues.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Its membership included organisers from former attempts to achieve institutional representation such as GLU and AUD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Opposition to pollution, use of nuclear power, NATO military action, and certain aspects of industrialised society were principal campaign issues.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party also championed sexual liberation and some of their members supported the abolition of age-of-consent laws.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The formation of a party was purportedly first discussed by movement leaders in 1978.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Important figures in the first years were – among others – Petra Kelly, Joschka Fischer, Gert Bastian, Lukas Beckmann, Rudolf Bahro, Joseph Beuys, Antje Vollmer, Herbert Gruhl, August Haußleiter, Luise Rinser, Dirk Schneider, Christian Ströbele, Jutta Ditfurth, Baldur Springmann and Werner Vogel.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1982, the conservative factions of the Greens broke away to form the Ecological Democratic Party (ÖDP).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They also tended to identify more closely with a culture of protest and civil disobedience, frequently clashing with police at demonstrations against nuclear weapons, nuclear energy, and the construction of a new runway (*Startbahn West*) at Frankfurt Airport.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Those who left the party at the time might have felt similarly about some of these issues, but did not identify with the forms of protest that Green party members took part in.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Among the important political issues at the time was the deployment of Pershing II IRBMs and nuclear-tipped cruise missiles by the U.S. and NATO on West German soil, generating strong opposition in the general population that found an outlet in mass demonstrations.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The newly formed party was able to draw on this popular movement to recruit support.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The state electoral success in Hesse and Hamburg saw the party holding the balance of power in both states.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In Hamburg the party won nine seats in the June 1982 election and made an offer of terms for confidence and supply to the Social Democrats, but these were rejected.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the following December election the Greens lost a seat and the SPD won an absolute majority.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In Hesse the Greens rejected the idea of cooperating with the SPD after the 1982 election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Another state election took place there the following year, resulting in the Greens losing two seats but no party achieving a majority.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Following the election the state Greens voted to accept a confidence and supply agreement with the Social Democrats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Despite this negotiations immediately commenced over terms for a coalition agreement.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Although the party's Bundestag faction had limited success in legislating during the new MPs' first term, they were able to influence debate inside and outside parliament through proposing bills and asking questions.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, the faction's efforts were disrupted by the attempt to implement rotation of members halfway through their terms as had been planned before the 1983 election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] All elected Bundestag members except Petra Kelly stepped down to enable rotation, however of the seven Green MEPs elected in the 1984 European election only three resigned from their roles.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The rotation stipulation was subsequently abolished, however the departure of many Bundestag members who had received significant media attention upon their entry to parliament led to reduced press interest in the parliamentary faction's work.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, elections in 1985 brought mixed results.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Contrastingly, in the West Berlin elections, after the SPD rejected the Alternative List's terms for a confidence and supply agreement before polling day, the SPD scored their worst post-war result of 32.4 percent, whilst the Greens almost doubled their vote to 10.6 percent and took 15 seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Whilst the SPD won 52.1 percent of the vote, the Greens failed to meet the electoral threshold with 4.6 percent.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Meanwhile, in local elections in Hesse both the SPD and Greens made gains, with the vote of the latter rising to 7.1 percent.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Shortly after Börner offered a coalition deal to the Greens which included the position of environment and energy minister.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Joschka Fischer took up the ministerial post, whilst Marita Haibach was made secretary of state for woman's affairs.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the federal party conference in Offenburg in December, the party's fundi faction, which had been hostile to the coalition agreement, took control of the party's executive.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1986, the intra-party conflict reduced somewhat.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A party conference in Hanover that Easter voted for an immediate end to nuclear power and the end of the coalition in Hesse.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] These attacks limited the party's gains to 0.6 percent of the vote, failing to add to the 11 seats won at the previous state election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, in the Bavarian state election the party entered parliament for the first time, winning 7.5 percent of the vote and 15 seats, whilst in the Hamburg elections an all-female list secured 10.4 percent of votes and 13 seats, whilst neither the CDU or SPD secured a parliamentary majority.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Around this time, Joschka Fischer emerged as the unofficial leader of the party, which he remained until resigning all leadership posts following the 2005 federal election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Following the federal election, factional tensions over strategy re-emerged.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Hesse party withdrew from their coalition with the SPD, over the same nuclear enrichment plant which had led to the collapse of the previous confidence and supply agreement.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the subsequent 1987 Hessian state election, the SPD vote declined, leading to a coalition of Christian Democrats and Free Democrats entering government, but the Green vote increased to 9.4 percent, securing them 10 seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the Hamburg election held to resolve the deadlock resulting from the previous year's poll, the Green vote dropped to 7.1 percent, losing them five seats, whilst the SPD and FDP were able to form a coalition.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Meanwhile in Rhineland-Palatinate the Greens entered parliament for the first time, taking 5.9 percent of the vote and six seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Later that year in state elections in Schleswig-Holstein the state Green party, which was opposed to participating in any coalition, failed to enter parliament and won only 3.9 percent of the vote, whilst in Bremen they almost doubled their vote to 10.2 percent and won ten seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Tensions were further inflamed by the killing of two police officers and injury of nine others by autonomist activists at a protest at Frankfurt Airport.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Whilst the bulk of the party condemned the killings, some on the left including Ditfurth and Thomas Ebermann did not.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The growing disagreements at the federal level resulted in a crisis meeting in December 1987, following by a perspective congress in June 1988.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens were the target of attempts by the East German secret police to enlist the cooperation of members who were willing to align the party with the agenda of the German Democratic Republic.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party ranks included several politicians who were later discovered to have been Stasi agents, including Bundestag representative Dirk Schneider, European Parliament representative Brigitte Heinrich, and Red Army Faction defense lawyer Klaus Croissant.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Greens politician and Bundestag representative Gert Bastian was also a founding member of Generals for Peace, a pacifist group created and funded by the Stasi, the revelation of which may have contributed to the murder-suicide in which he killed his partner and Greens founder Petra Kelly.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A study commissioned by the Greens determined that 15 to 20 members intimately cooperated with the Stasi and another 450 to 500 had been informants.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Until 1987, the Greens included a faction involved in pedophile activism, the *SchwuP* short for *Arbeitsgemeinschaft "Schwule, Päderasten und Transsexuelle"* (approx.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] *working group "Gays, Pederasts and Transsexuals"*).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This faction campaigned for repealing § 176 of the German penal code, dealing with child sexual abuse.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This group was controversial within the party itself, and was seen as partly responsible for the poor election result of 1985.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This controversy re-surfaced in 2013 and chairwoman Claudia Roth stated she welcomed an independent scientific investigation on the extent of influence pedophile activists had on the party in the mid-1980s.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In November 2014, the political scientist Franz Walter presented the final report about his research on a press conference.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 1990 federal elections, taking place post-reunified Germany, the Greens in the West did not pass the 5% limit required to win seats in the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It was only due to a temporary modification of German election law, applying the five-percent "hurdle" separately in East and West Germany, that the Greens acquired any parliamentary seats at all.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This happened because in the new states of Germany, the Greens, in a joint effort with Alliance 90, a heterogeneous grouping of civil rights activists, were able to gain more than 5% of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Some critics attribute this poor performance to the reluctance of the campaign to cater to the prevalent mood of nationalism, instead focusing on subjects such as global warming.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A campaign poster at the time proudly stated, "Everyone is talking about Germany; we're talking about the weather!", paraphrasing a popular slogan of Deutsche Bundesbahn, the German national railway.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party also opposed imminent reunification that was in process, instead wanting to initiate debates on ecology and nuclear issues before reunification causing a drop in support in Western Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] After the 1994 federal election; however, the merged party returned to the Bundestag, and the Greens received 7.3% of the vote nationwide and 49 seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 1998 federal election, despite a slight fall in their percentage of the vote (6.7%), the Greens retained 47 seats and joined the federal government for the first time in 'Red-Green' coalition government with the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Joschka Fischer became Vice-Chancellor of Germany and foreign minister in the new government, which had two other Green ministers (Andrea Fischer, later Renate Künast, and Jürgen Trittin).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Almost immediately the party was plunged into a crisis by the question of German participation in the NATO actions in Kosovo.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Numerous anti-war party members resigned their party membership when the first post-war deployment of German troops in a military conflict abroad occurred under a Red-Green government, and the party began to experience a long string of defeats in local and state-level elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 2001, the party experienced a further crisis as some Green Members of Parliament refused to back the government's plan of sending military personnel to help with the 2001 invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Chancellor Gerhard Schröder called a vote of confidence, tying it to his strategy on the war.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Four Green MPs and one Social Democrat voted against the government, but Schröder was still able to command a majority.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] On the other hand, the Greens achieved a major success as a governing party through the 2000 decision to phase out the use of nuclear energy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Minister of Environment, Nature Conservation and Nuclear Safety Jürgen Trittin reached an agreement with energy companies on the gradual phasing out of the country's nineteen nuclear power plants and a cessation of civil usage of nuclear power by 2020.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This was authorised through the Nuclear Exit Law.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Based on an estimate of 32 years as the normal period of operation for a nuclear power plant, the agreement defines precisely how much energy a power plant is allowed to produce before being shut down.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Despite the crises of the preceding electoral period, in the 2002 federal election, the Greens increased their total to 55 seats (in a smaller parliament) and 8.6%.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens benefited from increased inroads among traditionally left-wing demographics which had benefited from Green-initiated legislation in the 1998–2002 term, such as environmentalists (Renewable Energies Act) and LGBT groups (Registered Partnership Law).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Perhaps most important for determining the success of both the Greens and the SPD was the increasing threat of war in Iraq, which was highly unpopular with the German public, and helped gather votes for the parties which had taken a stand against participation in this war.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] One internal issue in 2002 was the failed attempt to settle a long-standing discussion about the question of whether members of parliament should be allowed to become members of the party executive.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Two party conventions declined to change the party statute.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The necessary majority of two-thirds was missed by a small margin.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] As a result, former party chairpersons Fritz Kuhn and Claudia Roth (who had been elected to parliament that year) were no longer able to continue in their executive function and were replaced by former party secretary general Reinhard Bütikofer and former Bundestag member Angelika Beer.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party then held a member referendum on this question in the spring of 2003 which changed the party statute.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Now members of parliament may be elected for two of the six seats of the party executive, as long as they are not ministers or caucus leaders.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] 57% of all party members voted in the member referendum, with 67% voting in favor of the change.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The referendum was only the second in the history of Alliance 90/The Greens, the first having been held about the merger of the Greens and Alliance 90.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 2004, after Angelika Beer was elected to the European Parliament, Claudia Roth was elected to replace her as party chair.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The November 2003 party convention was held in Dresden and decided the election platform for the 2004 European Parliament elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The German Green list for these elections was headed by Rebecca Harms (then leader of the Green party in Lower Saxony) and Daniel Cohn-Bendit, previously Member of the European Parliament for The Greens of France.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The November 2003 convention is also noteworthy because it was the first convention of a German political party ever to use an electronic voting system.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens gained a record 13 of Germany's 99 seats in these elections, mainly due to the perceived competence of Green ministers in the federal government and the unpopularity of the Social Democratic Party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In early 2005, the Greens were the target of the German Visa Affair 2005, instigated in the media by the Christian Democratic Union (CDU).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the end of April 2005, they celebrated the decommissioning of the Obrigheim nuclear power station.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They also continue to support a bill for an Anti-Discrimination Law (Allgemeines Gleichbehandlungsgesetz) in the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In May 2005, the only remaining state-level red-green coalition government lost the vote in the North Rhine-Westphalia state election, leaving only the federal government with participation of the Greens (apart from local governments).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the early 2005 federal election the party incurred very small losses and achieved 8.1% of the vote and 51 seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, due to larger losses of the SPD, the previous coalition no longer had a majority in the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] For almost two years after the federal election in 2005, the Greens were not part of any government at the state or federal level.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In June 2007, the Greens in Bremen entered into a coalition with the Social Democratic Party (SPD) following the 2007 Bremen state election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In April 2008, following the 2008 Hamburg state election, the Green-Alternative List (GAL) in Hamburg entered into a coalition with the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), the first such state-level coalition in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Although the GAL had to agree to the deepening of the Elbe River, the construction of a new coal-fired power station and two road projects they had opposed, they also received some significant concessions from the CDU.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] These included reforming state schools by increasing the number of primary school educational stages, the restoration of trams as public transportation in the city-state, and more pedestrian-friendly real estate development.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] On 29 November 2010, the coalition collapsed, resulting in an election that was won by SPD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Following the Saarland state election of August 2009, The Greens held the balance of power after a close election where no two-party coalitions could create a stable majority government.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In June 2010, in the first state election following the victory of the CDU/CSU and FDP in the 2009 federal election, the "black-yellow" CDU-FDP coalition in North Rhine-Westphalia under Jürgen Rüttgers lost its majority.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] So a red-green government in a state where it was defeated under Peer Steinbrück in 2005 came into office again on 14 June 2010 with the election of Hannelore Kraft as minister-president (Cabinet Kraft I).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens founded the first international chapter of a German political party in the U.S. on 13 April 2008 at the Goethe-Institut in Washington D.C.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In March 2011 (two weeks after the Fukushima nuclear disaster had begun), the Greens made large gains in Rhineland-Palatinate and in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In Baden-Württemberg they became the senior partner in a governing coalition for the first time.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Winfried Kretschmann is now the first Green to serve as Minister-President of a German State (Cabinet Kretschmann I and II).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Polling data from August 2011 indicated that one in five Germans supported the Greens.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] From 4 October 2011 to 4 September 2016, the party was represented in all state parliaments.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Like the Social Democrats, the Greens backed Chancellor Angela Merkel on most bailout votes in the German parliament during her second term, saying their pro-European stances overrode party politics.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Shortly before the elections, the party plummeted to a four-year low in the polls, undermining efforts by Peer Steinbrück's Social Democrats to unseat Merkel.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] While being in opposition on the federal level since 2005, the Greens have established themselves as a powerful force in Germany's political system.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] By 2016, the Greens had joined 11 out of 16 state governments in a variety of coalitions.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Over the years, they have built up an informal structure called G-coordination to organize interests between the federal party office, the parliamentary group in the Bundestag, and the Greens governing on the state level.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens remained the smallest of six parties in the Bundestag in the 2017 federal election, winning 8.9% of votes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] After the election, they entered into talks for a Jamaica coalition with the CDU and FDP.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Discussions collapsed after the FDP withdrew in November.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] After the federal election and unsuccessful Jamaica negotiations, the party held elections for two new co-leaders; incumbents Özdemir and Peter did not stand for re-election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Robert Habeck and Annalena Baerbock were elected with 81% and 64% of votes, respectively.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Habeck had served as deputy premier and environment minister in Schleswig-Holstein since 2012, while Baerbock had been a leading figure in the party's Brandenburg branch since 2009.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Their election was considered a break with tradition, as they were both members of the moderate wing.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens saw a major surge in support during the Bavarian and Hessian state elections in October 2018, becoming the second largest party in both.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They subsequently rose to second place behind the CDU/CSU in national polling, averaging between 17% and 20% over the next six months.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 2019 European Parliament election, the Greens achieved their best ever result in a national election, placing second with 20.5% of the vote and winning 21 seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] National polling released after the election showed a major boost for the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The first poll after the election, conducted by Forsa, showed the Greens in first place on 27%.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This was the first time the Greens had ever been in first place in a national opinion poll, and the first time in the history of the Federal Republic that any party other than the CDU/CSU or SPD had placed first in a national poll.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This trend continued as polls from May to July showed the CDU/CSU and Greens trading first place, after which point the CDU/CSU pulled ahead once more.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens continued to poll in the low 20% range into early 2020.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens recorded best-ever results in the Brandenburg (10.8%) and Saxony (8.6%) state elections in September 2019, and subsequently joined coalition governments in both states.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They suffered an unexpected decline in the Thuringian election in October, only narrowing retaining their seats with 5.2%.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the February 2020 Hamburg state election, the Greens became the second largest party, winning 24.2% of votes cast.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In March 2021, the Greens improved their performance in Baden-Württemberg, where they remained the strongest party with 32.6% of votes, and Rhineland-Palatinate, where they moved into third place with 9.3%.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Due to their sustained position as the second most popular party in national polling ahead of the September 2021 federal election, the Greens chose to forgo the traditional dual lead-candidacy in favour of selecting a single Chancellor candidate.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Co-leader Annalena Baerbock was announced as Chancellor candidate on 19 April and formally confirmed on 12 June with 98.5% approval.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens surged in opinion polls in late April and May, briefly surpassing the CDU as the most popular party in the country, but their numbers slipped back after Baerbock was caught up in several controversies.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Her personal popularity also fell below that of both Armin Laschet and Olaf Scholz, the Chancellor candidates for the CDU and SPD, respectively.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party's fortunes did not reverse even after the July floods, which saw climate change return as the most important issue among voters.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The situation worsened in August as the SPD surged into first place to the detriment of both the CDU and Greens.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens finished in third place in the 2021 federal election with 14.8% of votes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Though their best ever federal election result, it was considered a bitter disappointment in light of their polling numbers during the previous three years.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They entered coalition talks with the FDP and SPD, eventually joining a traffic light coalition under Chancellor Olaf Scholz which took office on 8 December 2021.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens have five ministers in the Scholz cabinet, including Robert Habeck as Vice-Chancellor and Annalena Baerbock as foreign minister.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Since party statute mandates that party leaders may not hold government office, Baerbock and Habeck stepped down after entering cabinet.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At a party conference in January 2022, Ricarda Lang and Omid Nouripour were elected to succeed them.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the time of her election, Lang was 28 years old, speaker for women's issues, and a former leader of the Green Youth.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] 46-year-old Nouripour was foreign affairs spokesman and a member of the Bundestag since 2006.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Of the new leaders, Lang is considered a representative of the party's left-wing, while Nouripour represents the right-wing.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Lang and Nouripour announced their resignations as party leaders in September 2024 after heavy defeats in the Saxony, Thuringia and Brandenburg state elections that month, as well as the earlier European Parliament election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In all three states, governing coalitions involving the Greens were not returned, and the party was wiped out in the latter two states while only narrowly retaining representation in Saxony.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the European elections, the Greens fell to fourth (behind the CDU/CSU, AfD and SPD) and lost 9 seats in the European parliament, falling to 12 seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party had fallen out of five state governments (additionally Berlin and Hesse) since entering the federal governing coalition in 2021.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Analysts pointed to its participation in the federal government requiring it to take stances that are contrary to its traditional clean-energy and pacifist ideals, as well as a stark collapse in support with young voters.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Felix Banaszak and Franziska Brantner elected as co-leaders in November 2024.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] During the 2024 government crisis, in which the FDP left the traffic light coalition, the Greens stayed in a red-green minority coalition.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party abstained in the succeeding vote of no confidence, ensuring the government's collapse and the calling of the 2025 federal election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party chose incumbent Vice Chancellor Robert Habeck as their chancellor candidate for the 2025 federal election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens would go on to lose 33 seats in that election, garnering 11.6% of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The unpopularity of the Scholz cabinet has been credited with the result, although this was still the party's second best ever result.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The morning after the election, Habeck announced his withdrawal from the party's leadership.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The other co-candidate for The Greens, Annalena Baerbock, as well as former party leader Ricarda Lang, were expected to become the next party leaders in the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party's main ideological trends are green politics and social liberalism.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party has also been described as left-libertarian, and influenced by the postmaterialist left.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party's political position is generally described to be centre-left, while others describe the party as centrist or left-wing.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens originated as a left-wing protest party in the 1980s but have since evolved into a centre-left party, especially after merging with Alliance 90 in 1993.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The West German Greens played a crucial role in the development of green politics in Europe, with their original program outlining "four principles: ecological, social, grassroots, and non-violent".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Initially ideologically heterogenous, the party took up a position on the radical left in its early years, which were dominated by conflicts between the more left-wing *Fundi* (fundamentalist) and more moderate *Realo* (realist) factions.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Writing in the late 1980s, Sara Parkin characterised the factional divides in the party as occurring along three axes: the strategic divide between fundis and realos, the left–right political spectrum, and the existence of affinity groups.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] From this view, watering down a radical worldview risked a failure to take sufficiently drastic action in the face of environmental crisis.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] As Kelly put it, "It does not help us in any way if we begin accepting lower and safer levels of, for example, radioactivity...
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] We must speak out clear, loudly and courageously, if we know there are no safe levels".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Fundis also express concern about losing touch with grassroots activists, and in Germany particularly emphasise solidarity with groups they consider to be victimised by the state, resulting in them being less likely to condemn use of violence by protest movements than realos.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] According to Parkin, fundis were particularly prevalent on state and federal committees and executive bodies and formed a minority in parliamentary parties.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Realos are reformists who argue that the appropriate response to ecological crisis is to take action within the existing political system, and that to do otherwise is to condemn the green movement to irrelevance.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] They stress the importance of going beyond critique to develop practical solutions to environmental and other problems.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] They additionally advocate for professionalisation of the party organisation, and believe in maintaining a certain distance from social movements.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In Schily's case the development of his beliefs led him to leave the Greens for the SPD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Other realos like Christa Vennegerts argued for clarification and development of policies in key areas such as economics and defence.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Other Greens associated with the realo faction include Daniel Cohn-Bendit, Wolf-Dieter Hasenclever, Waltraud Schoppe, Rezzo Schlauch and Hubert Kleinert, as well as the thinktank the Institute for Social-Ecological Research.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] According to Parkin realos constituted the majority of party members and elected officials.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] This group was particularly associated with Antje Vollmer and stressed a stronger concentration on ecological issues.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Michal Bondemann suggested that this faction reflected the development of a party bureaucracy, cadre and career politicians in the Greens.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In terms of the left-right spectrum, the left wing of the party was strengthened by an influx of radical left activists into the party when it was formed.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Whilst some contributed to the development of new perspectives through dialogue with environmental activists, others hewed closer to their pre-existing ideology whilst within the party, such as the Z Group which had originated as a breakaway from the Communist League.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Z Group was subject to a party tribunal in 1981 considering whether they should be expelled, which eventually decided against this.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Prominent figures in this group included Thomas Ebermann and Rainer Trampert.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Ebermann and Trampert were both leftists and fundis, as was Jutta Ditfurth.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Other more moderate eco-socialists were aligned with the realos on strategic questions.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] This faction, officially established in 1984, opposed socialism and social security.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] These conflicts became less significant as the party moved toward the political mainstream in the 1990s.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] This was mainly due to the weakening of the fundis leading to the realos establishing control of the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In 1988 accusations of financial irregularities within the party were made by the news magazine *Der Spiegel* and also by Cohn-Bendit.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Although an investigative commission rejected the claims in October, at party congress in Karlsruhe in December Ditfurth accused the realos of supplying false information to *Der Spiegel* in a speech which was poorly received by delegates.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The congress passed a motion of no confidence and the fundi controlled Federal Executive Committee resigned *en bloc*, resulting in the faction losing one of their biggest strongholds within the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Realo control over the party was secured after its poor performance in the first federal election in the reunified Germany in 1990, when the West and East German Greens ran separately and the former failed to cross the electoral threshold and elected any Bundestag members.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Paul Hockenos has suggested that this period saw the end of the fundi-realo dimension of struggle within the party, although left-right contestation continued.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] After this period, the party moved away from pacifism, supporting EU military cooperation and military interventions in Yugoslavia and Afghanistan, and watered down its commitment to other non-environmental issues such as feminism and social justice.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] During the 2021 federal election, the WZB Berlin Social Science Center classified the party as the most centrist of Germany's left-wing parties.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Annalena Baerbock campaigned from the left of the SPD, stating that the party's economic program is geared towards the "common good" while the SPD's no longer is.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party has a more pragmatic approach to workers' rights than the SPD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] On the other hand, the party clearly holds positions to the left of the SPD on issues such as fiscal discipline, particularly on the debt brake, the climate transition, and property expropriation in Berlin.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] They are focusing on environmentalist and socially progressive policies.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Emphasis is placed on mitigating climate change, reducing carbon emissions, and fostering sustainability and environmentally-friendly practices.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] They support equality, social justice, and humanitarian responses to events such as the European migrant crisis.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Their fiscal platform is flexible and seeks to balance social, economic, and environmental interests.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party is strongly pro-European, advocating European federalism, and promotes wider international cooperation, including strengthening existing alliances.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Starting from the leadership of Annalena Baerbock and Robert Habeck, commentators have observed the Greens taking a pragmatic, moderate approach to work with parties from across the political spectrum.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Baerbock described their stances and style as a form of "radical realism" attempting to reconcile principles with practical politics.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] At the same time, the party has denounced populism and division, and placed rhetorical emphasis on optimism and cross-party cooperation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Accompanied by record high popularity and election results, this led some to suggest that the Greens were filling a gap in the political centre, which was left by the declining popularity of the CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party has economically left-liberal views.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens are regarded as taking a Atlanticist line on defense and pushing for a stronger common EU foreign policy, especially against Russia and China.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Former Green Party co-leader Annalena Baerbock proposed a post-pacifist foreign policy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] She supports eastward expansion of NATO and has considered the number of UN resolutions critical of Israel as "absurd compared to resolutions against other states." The party's program included references to NATO as an "indispensable" part of European security.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens have promised to abolish the contested Nord Stream 2 pipeline to ship Russian natural gas to Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party criticized the EU's investment deal with China.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] It describes China as a "systematic rival", though the party also favors cooperation with China to fight climate change.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In 2016, the Greens criticised Germany's defense plan with Saudi Arabia, which has been waging war in Yemen and has been accused of massive human rights violations.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party remains divided over issues such as nuclear disarmament and U.S. nuclear weapons on German territory.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Some Greens want Germany to sign the United Nations' Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Ever since the party's inception, The Greens have been concerned with the immediate halt of construction or operation of all nuclear power stations.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] As an alternative, they promote a shift to non-nuclear renewable energy and a comprehensive program of energy conservation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In 1986, large parts of Germany were covered with radioactive contamination from the Chernobyl disaster and Germans went to great lengths to deal with the contamination.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Germany's anti-nuclear stance was strengthened.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] From the mid-1990s onwards, anti-nuclear protests were primarily directed against transports of radioactive waste in "CASTOR" containers.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] After the Chernobyl disaster, the Greens became more radicalised and resisted compromise on the nuclear issue.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] During the 1990s, a re-orientation towards a moderate program occurred, with concern about global warming and ozone depletion taking a more prominent role.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] During the federal red-green government (1998–2005) many people became disappointed with what they saw as excessive compromise on key Greens policies.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The central idea of green politics is sustainable development.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The concept of environmental protection is the cornerstone of Alliance 90/The Greens policy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In particular, the economic, energy and transport policy claims are in close interaction with environmental considerations.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens acknowledge the natural environment as a high priority and animal protection should be enshrined as a national objective in constitutional law.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] An effective environmental policy would be based on a common environmental code, with the urgent integration of a climate change bill.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] During the red-green coalition (1998–2005) a policy of agricultural change was launched labeled as a paradigm shift in agricultural policy towards a more ecological friendly agriculture, which needs to continue.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens have praised the European Green Deal, which aims to make the EU climate neutral by 2050.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Climate change is at the center of all policy considerations.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] This includes environmental policy and safety and social aspects.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The plans of the Alliance 90/The Greens provide a climate change bill laying down binding reductions to greenhouse gas emissions in Germany by 2020 restricting emissions to minus 40 percent compared to 1990.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Alliance 90/The Greens supports the eventual federalization of the European Union into a Federal European Republic (German: *Föderale Europäische Republik*), i.e. a single federal European sovereign state.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] A similarly high priority is given to transport policy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The switch from a traveling allowance to a mobility allowance, which is paid regardless of income to all employees, replacing company car privileges.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The truck toll will act as a climate protection instrument internalizing the external costs of transport.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Railway should be promoted in order to achieve the desired environmental objectives and the comprehensive care of customers.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The railway infrastructure is to remain permanently in the public sector, allowing a reduction in expenditure on road construction infrastructure.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens want to control privileges on kerosene and for international flights, introduce an air ticket levy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Fossil fuels such as heavy oil or diesel shall be replaced by emission-neutral fuels and green propulsion systems in order to make shipping climate-neutral in the long term.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] For many years, the Green Party has advocated against the "Ehegattensplitting" policy, under which the incomes of married couples are split for taxation purposes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In its 2013 platform, the Green Party successfully advocated for a minimum wage of 8.50 Euro per hour, which was implemented on 1 January 2015.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] It continues to press for higher minimum wages.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens want the starting retirement age to remain 67, but with some qualifications – for example, a provision for partial retirement.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party supports and has supported various forms of rent regulation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] During the 2021 election, the party called for rent hikes to be capped at 2.5% per year.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens support progressive taxation and is critical of FDP efforts to cut taxes for top earners.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Green Party supports the implementation of quotas in executive boards, the policy of equal pay for equal work, and continuing the fight against domestic violence.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] According to its website, the Green Party "fights for the acceptance and against the exclusion of homosexuals, bisexuals, intersex- and transgender people and others".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In order to recognize the political persecution that LGBT+ people face abroad, the Green Party wants to extend asylum to LGBTQIA+ people abroad.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The policy change was sponsored primarily by Volker Beck, one of the Party's most prominent gay members.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Because of the extensive support the Green Party has given the LGBTQIA+ community since its conception, many LGBTQIA+ people vote for the Green Party even if their political ideology does not quite align otherwise.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party supports the legalization and regulation of cannabis and was the sponsor of the 2015 proposed iteration of the German cannabis control bill.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Furthermore, the Greens support research on the drug and the use of marijuana for medicinal purposes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] A 2000 study by the Infratest Dimap political research company has suggested the Green voter demographic includes those on higher incomes (e.g. above €2,000/month) and the party's support is less among households with lower incomes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The same polling research also concluded that the Greens received fewer votes from the unemployed and general working population, with business people favouring the party as well as the centre-right liberal Free Democratic Party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] According to the Infratest Dimap political research company for the ARD, the Greens received more voters from the age group 34–42 than any other age group and that the young were generally more supportive of the party than the old.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens have more support concentrated in metropolitan areas rather than rural areas, except for a small number of rural areas with critical local environmental concerns, such as strip mining or radioactive waste deposits.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The cities of Bonn, Cologne, Stuttgart, Berlin, Hamburg, Frankfurt and Munich have among the highest percentages of Green voters in the country.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Large towns with Green mayors as of March 2026 include Hanover, Kassel, Munich and Münster.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party has a lower level of support in the states of the former German Democratic Republic (East Germany); nonetheless, the party is currently represented in every state Landtag except Brandenburg, Saarland, and Thuringia.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Its name reflects its resistance to the mainstream policies of Angela Merkel and her slogan *Alternativlosigkeit* (lit.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] 'alternative-less-ness', a German version of "there is no alternative").
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Established in April 2013, AfD narrowly missed the 5% electoral threshold to sit in the Bundestag during the 2013 federal election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party won seven seats in the 2014 European Parliament election in Germany as a member of the European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2021 federal election, AfD dropped to being the fifth-largest party in the 20th Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Following the 2025 federal election, it became the second-largest party and the largest opposition party in the 21st Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD was founded by Gauland, Bernd Lucke, and former members of the Christian Democratic Union of Germany (CDU) to oppose the policies of the eurozone as a right-wing and moderately Eurosceptic alternative to the centre-right but pro-European CDU.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party presented itself as an economically liberal, Eurosceptic, and conservative movement in its early years.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD subsequently moved further to the right, and expanded its policies under successive leaderships to include opposition to immigration, Islam, and the European Union.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Since 2015, with the beginning of the refugee crisis in Europe, AfD's ideology has been characterised by German nationalism, *völkisch* nationalism (ethno-nationalism), right-wing populism, and national conservatism.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] It has a policy focus on opposing Islam, opposing immigration into Germany, especially Muslim immigration into Germany, welfare chauvinism, Euroscepticism, denial of human-caused global warming, and supporting closer relations with Russia.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] They have been observed by various state offices for the protection of the constitution since 2018.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD's leadership has denied that the party is racist and has been internally divided on whether to endorse such groups.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In January 2022, after a failed power struggle, party leader Jörg Meuthen resigned his party chairmanship with immediate effect and left AfD, stating that the party had moved far to the right with totalitarian traits and in large parts was no longer based on Germany's liberal democratic basic order.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Lucke had left the party in 2015 with a similar view.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In 2023, the Young Alternative for Germany was officially categorized by the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution (BfV) as a confirmed extremist organisation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In 2025, the BfV officially classified AfD as a "confirmed right-wing extremist endeavor," which allows authorities to increase surveillance, and permits the use of informants and monitoring of communications, though this classification was suspended following a 2026 court injunction.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2021 federal elections, AfD fell from third to fifth place overall but made gains in the eastern states.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the former East Berlin, it came in second after SPD with 20.5% of the vote; in the west, it came in fifth with 8.4% of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2025 German federal election, AfD received a record 20.8% of the vote and ended in second place behind CDU/CSU.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Their manifesto was endorsed by several economists, journalists, and business leaders, and stated that the eurozone had proven to be "unsuitable" as a currency area and that southern European states were "sinking into poverty under the competitive pressure of the euro".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Some candidates of what would become AfD sought election in Lower Saxony as part of the *Electoral Alternative 2013* in alliance with the Free Voters, an association participating in local elections without specific federal or foreign policies, and received 1% of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In February 2013, the group decided to found a new party to compete in the 2013 federal election; according to a leaked email from Lucke, the Free Voters leadership declined to join forces.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party was founded on 6 February 2013.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 14 April 2013, the AfD announced its presence to the wider public when it held its first convention in Berlin, elected the party leadership, and adopted a party platform.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Bernd Lucke, the entrepreneur Frauke Petry and Konrad Adam were elected as speakers.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD's federal board also chose Alexander Gauland, Roland Klaus, and Patricia Casale as its three deputy speakers.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party elected the treasurer Norbert Stenzel and the three assessors Irina Smirnova, Beatrix Diefenbach, and Wolf-Joachim Schünemann.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The economist Joachim Starbatty, along with Jörn Kruse, Helga Luckenbach, Dirk Meyer, and Roland Vaubel, were elected to the party's scientific advisory board.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Between 31 March and 12 May 2013 AfD founded affiliates in all 16 states of Germany in order to participate in the federal elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 15 June 2013 the Young Alternative for Germany was founded in Darmstadt as the AfD's youth organisation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] During the British prime minister David Cameron's visit to Germany in April 2013, the British Conservative Party was reported to have contacted both AfD and the Free Voters to discuss possible cooperation, supported by the European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR) group of the European Parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In June 2013 Bernd Lucke gave a question and answer session organized by the Conservative Party-allied Bruges Group think tank in Portcullis House, London.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In a detailed report in the conservative *Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung* in April 2013, the paper's Berlin-based political correspondent Majid Sattar revealed that the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) and CDU had conducted opposition research to blunt the growth and attraction of AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Advocating the abolition of the euro, AfD took a more radical stance than the Free Voters.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The Pirate Party Germany opposed any coalition with AfD at their 2013 spring convention.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD did not regard itself as a splinter party from the CDU, as its early membership also contained a former state leader from the Free Democratic Party and members of the Federation of Independent Voters, a pressure group of independents and small business owners.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 22 September 2013 AfD won 4.7% of the votes in the 2013 federal election, just missing the 5% barrier to enter the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party won about 2 million party list votes and 810,000 constituency votes, which was 1.9% of the total of these votes cast across Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD did not participate in the 2013 Bavaria state election held on 15 September.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party gained parliamentary representation for the first time in the state parliament of Hesse, with the defection of Jochen Paulus from the Free Democratic Party to AfD in early May 2013; he was not re-elected and left office in January 2014.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2013 Hesse state election held on 22 September, the same day as the 2013 federal election, AfD failed to gain representation with just 4% of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In early 2014, the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany ruled the proposed 3% vote hurdle for representation in the European elections unconstitutional, and the 2014 European Parliament election became the first run in Germany without a barrier for representation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD held a party conference on 25 January 2014 in Aschaffenburg, northwest Bavaria.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The conference chose the slogan *Mut zu Deutschland* ("Courage [to stand up] for Germany") to replace the former slogan *Mut zur Wahrheit* (lit.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] 'Courage [to speak] the truth', or more succinctly, "Telling it as it is"), which prompted disagreement among the federal board that the party could be seen as too anti-European.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] A compromise was reached by using the slogan "MUT ZU D*EU*TSCHLAND", with the "EU" in "DEUTSCHLAND" encircled by the 12 stars of the European flag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The conference elected the top six candidates for the European elections on 26 January 2014 and met again the following weekend to choose the remaining euro candidates.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Candidates from 7th–28th place on the party list were selected in Berlin on 1 February.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Party chairman Bernd Lucke was elected as lead candidate.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In February 2014, AfD officials said they had discussed alliances with the British anti-EU UK Independence Party (UKIP), which Lucke and the federal board of AfD opposed, and also with the European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR) group, to which Britain's Conservative Party belongs.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In April 2014 Hans-Olaf Henkel, AfD's second candidate on the European election list, ruled out forming a group with UKIP. stating that he saw the Conservatives as the preferred partner in the European Parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 10 May 2014 Lucke had been in talks with the Czech and Polish member parties of the ECR group.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2014 European Parliament election on 25 May, AfD came in fifth place in Germany, with 7.1% of the national vote (2,065,162 votes), and seven Members of the European parliament (MEPs).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 12 June 2014, it was announced that AfD had been accepted into the ECR group in the European Parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The official vote result was not released to the public, but figures of 29 votes for and 26 against were reported by the membership.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The inclusion of AfD in the ECR group was said to have caused mild tensions between the German chancellor Angela Merkel and the British prime minister David Cameron.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 31 August AfD received 9.7% of the vote in the 2014 Saxony state election, winning 14 seats in the Landtag of Saxony.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 14 September, AfD obtained 10.6% of the vote in the 2014 Thuringian and 12.2% in the Brandenburg state election, winning 11 seats in both state parliaments.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 15 February 2015 AfD won 6.1% of the vote in the Hamburg state election, gaining the mandate for eight seats in the Hamburg Parliament, winning their first seats in a western German state.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 10 May 2015, AfD secured in the 5.5% of the vote in the 2015 Bremen state election gaining representation in their fifth state parliament on a 50% turnout.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] After months of factional infighting and a cancelled party gathering in June 2015, Frauke Petry was elected on 4 July 2015 as the *de facto* principal speaker of the party with 60% of the member votes ahead of Bernd Lucke at a party congress in Essen.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Petry was a member of the national-conservative faction of AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Her leadership was widely seen as heralding a shift of the party to the right to focus more on issues such as immigration, Islam, and strengthening ties to Russia, a shift which was claimed by Lucke as turning the party into a "Pegida party".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the following week, five MEPs exited the party on 7 July, the only remaining MEPs being Beatrix von Storch and Marcus Pretzell, and Lucke announced on 8 July 2015 that he was resigning from AfD, citing the rise of xenophobic and pro-Russian sentiments in the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] At a meeting of members of the Wake-up call (Weckruf 2015) group on 19 July 2015, AfD founder Bernd Lucke and former AfD members announced they would form a new party, the Alliance for Progress and Renewal, under the founding principles of AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The split off party was eventually renamed the Liberal Conservative Reformers, but had little electoral success.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In February 2016 AfD announced a cooperation pact with the Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 8 March 2016, the bureau of the ECR group began motions to exclude AfD from their group due to its links with the far-right FPÖ, inviting the two remaining AfD MEPs to leave the group by 31 March, with a motion of exclusion to be tabled on 12 April if they refuse to leave voluntarily.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] While von Storch left the ECR group on 8 April to join the Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy group, Pretzell let himself be expelled on 12 April.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] With the European migrant crisis remaining the dominant national issue, elections on 13 March were held in the three states of Baden-Württemberg, Rhineland-Palatinate, and Saxony-Anhalt, and saw the AfD receiving double-digit percentages of the vote in all three states.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2016 Saxony-Anhalt state election, AfD reached second place in the Landtag, receiving 24.2% of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2016 Baden-Württemberg state election, AfD achieved third place, with 15.1% of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2016 Rhineland-Palatinate state election, AfD again reached third place, with 12.6% of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In Angela Merkel's home state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, her CDU was beaten into third place following a strong showing of AfD, who contested at state level for the first time, to claim the second-highest polling with 20.8% of the vote in the 2016 state election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Rising support for AfD meant that The Greens and the NDP failed to reach the 5% threshold to qualify for seats in the Landtag of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, and consequently lost their seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2016 Berlin state election, which AfD also contested for the first time, the party achieved a vote of 14.2%, making them the fifth largest party represented in the state assembly.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Their vote seems to have come equally from the SPD and CDU, whose votes declined 6.7% and 5.7%, respectively.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] At the party congress held on 30 April to 1 May 2016, AfD adopted a policy platform based upon opposition to Islam, calling for the ban of Islamic symbols including burqas, minarets, and *adhan* (call to prayer), using the slogan "Islam is not a part of Germany".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] At the party conference in April 2017, Frauke Petry announced that she would not run as the party's main candidate for the 2017 federal election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] This announcement grew out of internal power struggle as the party's support had fallen in polls from 15% in the summer of 2016 to 7% just before the conference.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Björn Höcke from the far-right wing of the party and Petry were attempting to push each other out of the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Petry's decision was partly seen as a step to avoid a vote at the conference on the issue of her standing.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party chose Alexander Gauland, a stark conservative who worked as an editor and was a former member of the CDU, to lead the party in the elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Gauland supported the retention of Höcke's party membership.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Alice Weidel, who is perceived as more moderate and neoliberal, was elected as his running mate.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2017 federal election AfD won 12.6% of the vote and received 94 seats; this was the first time it had won seats in the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] It won three constituency seats, which would have been enough to qualify for proportionally-elected seats in any event.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Under a long-standing law intended to benefit regional parties, any party that wins at least three constituency seats qualifies for its share of proportionally-elected seats, regardless of vote share.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] She also said that she would be leaving the party at some future date.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Petry formed the Blue Party in September 2017.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Four members of AfD in the Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania legislature, including Bernhard Wild, also left the party to form Citizens for Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, which folded in December 2018.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 6 November 2019 Petry announced that the Blue Party would dissolve by the end of the year.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In 2018 André Poggenburg, AfD's regional leader of the eastern Saxony-Anhalt state, resigned his post after making racist remarks concerning Turks and immigrants with dual citizenship.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In 2019, Poggenburg started a new far-right party, *Aufbruch deutscher Patrioten – Mitteldeutschland* (ADPM), which he left in August 2019 after his internal call to dissolve ADPM and to support AfD in the upcoming state elections of fall 2019 was denied.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Ahead of the 2021 federal election, AfD campaigned with the slogan "Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] But Normal" and took a position of opposing further lockdowns in response to the COVID-19 pandemic in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Having moved further right on economic issues and remaining strongly right on socio-cultural issues, despite attempts to normalize, AfD's manifesto for the federal election was deemed to be still too radical for the party to take part in government.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the federal election, AfD saw a dip in national vote share by getting 10.3% of the vote, compared to 12.6% in 2017; however, the party emerged as the largest in the states of Saxony and Thuringia, and saw a strong performance in eastern Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party's results drew a mixed analysis from AfD members and political commentators, the latter of whom attributed the slight decline to visible infighting, whereas AfD candidates such as Alice Weidel blamed media bias against the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The political scientist Kai Arzheimer commented that the result "wasn't any appreciable increase, but it wasn't a disaster for them." Arzheimer also posited that the result demonstrated that AfD had firmly established itself in German national politics but had not reached beyond its core support.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD's top candidates Tino Chrupalla and Weidel praised the result as "solid", while party spokesman Jörg Meuthen stated that the party should reevaluate the result and aim on "sending strong signals towards the center" to win back new voters.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD held their three seats in the 2022 Saarland state election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] At the same time, they lost all their seats in the 2022 Schleswig-Holstein state election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2022 Lower Saxony state election in October, AfD won 9 more seats compared to 2017 to a total of 18.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2023 Berlin repeat state election AfD recorded a small upswing by gaining 4 seats compared to the 2021 election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2023 Bremen state election AfD did not participate and lost all their seats, as the Bremen electoral committee had barred AfD from the election due to internal divisions that had resulted in them submitting two lists of candidates.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The Citizens in Rage, another right-wing party, participated instead; they received 10 seats (after having only one seat in 2019) in Bremen's state parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 25 June 2023, amidst rises in polls, Thuringia's AfD won its first district election in Sonneberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the run-off election held on 2 July, the AfD candidate Hannes Loth won against the independent politician Nils Naumann, becoming AfD's first ever mayor.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 8 October state elections, AfD significantly increased its share in Hesse where it became the second-biggest party (+9 seats) and in Bavaria, where it became the third (+10 seats).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Observers considered the increase of support for the AfD as not being limited to the local level.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Opinion polling for the 2025 German federal election conducted in early July 2023 showed that the AfD polled more than the SPD, achieving second place behind the CDU/CSU alliance.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The SPD co-leader said a ban should be considered if the AfD is categorized as a group of "proven Right-wing extremists" by the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Friedrich Merz, the CDU leader, warned that "banning parties has never actually solved political problems".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Germans are evenly split on a ban, with 47 per cent in favour and 47 per cent against; the ban is more popular in the west and among liberal Greens.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In December 2023 Tim Lochner of AfD was elected Mayor of Pirna (Saxony).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] He became the first mayor of a city with more than 20,000 inhabitants to be a member of the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In 2023, the AfD saw 86 violent attacks on AfD party representatives.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] This was more than on any other German party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In January 2024 Correctiv reported that members of AfD had secretly met with figures from the German and Austrian far-right in November 2023, in which they allegedly discussed a "remigration" plan for deporting immigrants, which could include naturalised German citizens.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Those present included the Identitarian activist Martin Sellner.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The AfD distanced itself from the meeting, saying it was not responsible for what was discussed and that its members had attended only in a personal capacity.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Alice Weidel parted ways with Roland Hartwig, an advisor who was present at the meeting.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The plan was condemned by German politicians, including Chancellor Olaf Scholz.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The report sparked protests against the AfD across Germany, with protestors calling for a ban of AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Subsequently, the AfD member Maximilian Krah got involved in controversy, prompting AfD to be expelled from the ID group, with EKRE supporting expulsion of Krah, but opposing the removal of the entire AfD delegation, and the FPÖ opposing the expulsion of AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 9 June 2024 AfD won 16% of the vote in the European Parliament elections, second only to the CDU/CSU and almost five percentage points more than in the 2019 election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD prevailed in all five former East German states.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] One of the party's leaders, Tino Chrupalla, hailed the results as "historic".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In an attempt to rejoin the ID group, the AfD replaced its controversial candidate Maximilian Krah with René Aust as head of the AfD delegation in the European Parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] However, AfD failed to join ID, or now named Patriots for Europe.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Instead, AfD formed the new ESN group which was composed predominantly of AfD members, as well as some other ethnonationalist parties across Europe.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2024 Thuringian state election, the AfD became the first far-right party in Germany since the Nazi Party to win a plurality of seats in a state election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The AfD also performed strongly in Brandenburg and Saxony.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 23 February 2025 AfD won 20.8% of the vote in the German federal election, second to the CDU/CSU.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] It gained 10.4 percentage points over the 2021 election result.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party won nearly a third of the votes in each of the East German states, the lowest being 32.5% in Brandenburg and the highest 38.5% in Thuringia, and won all but three constituency seats in the former East Germany (Potsdam, Erfurt and one of two seats in Leipzig).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the former West Germany, the party beat the SPD for second place by less than 0.5% of the vote and received more than 20% of the vote in two southwestern states: Saarland (21.6%) and Rhineland-Palatinate (20.1%).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In April 2025, for the first time in German history, AfD was ahead of the CDU/CSU (Union) in some opinion polls for the next federal election, while other polls put it on par with the Union or in second place.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Support for the CDU/CSU, an alliance that won the election, fell from 29% to 24%, while AfD rose by three percentage points from 22% to 25%, partially becoming the most popular party in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In May 2025 the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution (BfV) classified AfD as a "confirmed right-wing extremist endeavor".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In a 1,100-page classified and undisclosed report, BfV experts found that AfD is a "racist and anti-Muslim organisation".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The classification will allow German authorities to monitor AfD and possibly limit or halt public funding for it.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] It may also inspire its opponents to attempt to get it banned.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD leaders Alice Weidel and Tino Chrupalla said the decision was "clearly politically motivated" and was a "severe blow to German democracy".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] They argued that AfD is being discredited and persecuted by the government.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Chancellor Olaf Scholz said that BfV provided a "very detailed justification" for its decision and that proceedings to ban the AfD must not be rushed.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Several federal states in Germany have begun considering measures that would ban AfD members from being employed in jobs like civil servants, police officers, teachers or soldiers in response to the classification.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 4 May 2025 a poll conducted by Insa Polling Institute which surveyed 1,001 people found that 48% of them favour banning AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The poll also showed that 61% of participants consider AfD a "right-wing extremist” party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] A court in Cologne will start reviewing the case once BfV confirms that it has been notified of the lawsuit.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] Sieghard Knodel, a member of AfD in the Bundestag, announced his resignation from the party on 6 May 2025.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] He wrote in an email: "In light of the classification of the party as confirmed right-wing extremist by the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution, I must protect my private and business environment".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] He said that he would continue to serve as a non-attached member of parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] On May 8, the extremist classification of AfD was temporarily suspended by the BfV pending an official court judgement.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The AfD's leaders said that the decision was a "first important step" that would help "counter the accusation of right-wing extremism".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] The report by the BfV that led to the classification was later leaked to the public.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p01] In August, five direct and two reserve AfD candidates died within 14 days of each other ahead of local elections in North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD is broadly considered to be a right-wing and national-conservative movement in both socioeconomic and sociocultural terms.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Other commentators have categorized it as a radical right populist party or as "a typical radical right-wing populist party", with an emphasis on nativism.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Within its elected representation and grassroots membership, AfD has grown to contain interparty factions that range from more moderate conservatives to radicals.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] At that time, the party also advocated support for Swiss-style semi-direct democracy, major reforms to the eurozone, opposition to immigration, and opposed same-sex marriage.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] During this period, the party espoused economic liberal, ordoliberal, and national liberal policy stances.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Former party MEP Hans-Olaf Henkel likened AfD's early platform to the Conservative Party in Britain rather than hard Eurosceptic or nationalist parties such as the UK Independence Party or the National Front in France.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD was also compared to the Tea Party movement by some media outlets due to its campaigns against eurozone bailouts, although AfD's early leadership disputed this and said it was not looking to attract right-wing extremists into the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2015 more moderate members, including its founder and former chairman Bernd Lucke, left AfD after Frauke Petry was elected chairperson to found a new party, the Alliance for Progress and Renewal, which was renamed the Liberal Conservative Reformers in November 2016.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD underwent a further shift to the right after Petry left the party in 2017 and formed The Blue Party, following AfD's adoption of more hardline Islamophobic, anti-immigration positions, and historical revisionist remarks by leading AfD figures.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party now resembles other populist radical right parties in Europe but is somewhat unusual because it maintains visible ties to even more extreme groups.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party has been described by political scientists as more radical than many other European right-wing populist parties, including the Sweden Democrats, the Danish People's Party, and the Freedom Party of Austria.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has been described as, and accused of, containing members sympathetic to the Identitarian movement and Pegida.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD leadership has been split on whether to embrace these movements within the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In early March 2021 most of Germany's major media outlets reported that the *Bundesverfassungsschutz* had placed the whole AfD under surveillance as a "suspected extremist group".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In response to claims from AfD members that the move was intended to damage the party's chances in the 2021 German federal election, the agency stated it would not make public announcements regarding investigations into AfD or its candidates for the foreseeable future.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] After the revelations, the surveillance was blocked by the courts to give equal opportunities among political parties in a key election year.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2022 it was ruled that the BfV may classify and monitor the entire party as a suspected right-wing extremist group.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] A corresponding lawsuit by AfD was dismissed because "there were sufficient factual indications of anti-constitutional efforts within the AfD".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] On 26 April 2023 the BfV, after four years of investigations into the Young Alternative for Germany, categorized that group as a confirmed extremist organisation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] This allowed the chief of the BfV Thomas Haldenwang to place the youth wing under even more intensive surveillance than the tapping of phone and the use of undercover agents that had been the case until then.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2025, the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution officially classified AfD as a "confirmed right-wing extremist endeavor," which allows authorities to increase surveillance, and permits the use of informants and monitoring of communications.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The expertise by the BfV, that led to that classification, was later leaked to the public.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD is anti-communist and engaged in red-baiting by comparing Angela Merkel and her government to the secret police in East Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Some academics have described additional factions representing economic liberals or the Christian right.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The political author Jeffrey Gedmin has described the present incarnation of AfD as somewhat lacking in a consistent ideological vision and containing a broad church of members who are conservatives, social conservatives, radical-rightists, and others who do not present clear ideological narrative.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] He also described some of its core voter support as ranging from far-right nationalists to moderate but traditionalist and disaffected conservatives.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Over time a focus on German nationalism, on reclaiming Germany's sovereignty and national pride, especially in repudiation of Germany's culture of shame with regard to its Nazi past, became more central in AfD's ideology and a central plank in its populist appeals.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Petry, who led the moderate wing of the party, said that Germany should reclaim *völkisch* from its Nazi connotations, while the more right-wing Björn Höcke regularly speaks of the *Vaterland* ("fatherland") and *Volk* ("nation" or "people", but with a strong ethnic or racial connotation).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In January 2017 Höcke in a speech stated, in reference to the Berlin Holocaust Memorial, that "Germans are the only people in the world who plant a monument of shame in the heart of the capital" and criticised this "laughable policy of coming to terms with the past".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Höcke continued that Germany should make a "180 degree" turn with regard to its sense of national pride.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Some AfD members and candidates have expressed antisemitic attitudes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD leaders have repeatedly denied accusations of antisemitism.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] According to a study conducted by the Forsa Institute in 2019, while 2% of the German population agreed with the statement that "the Holocaust is propaganda of the Allied Powers", that proportion was 15% among AfD supporters.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The propaganda steamroller is getting stronger rather than weaker over the years, and in more and more countries the Jewish 'truth' about the Holocaust is being given legal protection.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2017, ten AfD Bundestag members were found to have participated in a closed Facebook group named "the Patriots" in which, among other things, antisemitic, racist, pro-Nazi and conspiratorial posts were widespread.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] One meme posted therein, which showed the Holocaust victim Anne Frank's face edited on a pizza box labelled with the German equivalent of "fresh from the oven", gained particular media attention.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2023 Felix Klein, the Federal Government Commissioner for Jewish Life in Germany and the Fight against antisemitism, stated that leading forces within AfD relativize the Holocaust and that the party condones antisemitism.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Josef Schuster, President of the Central Council of Jews in Germany, stated in 2024 that he is "concerned that the AfD would deliberately act against Jewish life, if it fits into their concept", and that the party offers antisemites a home.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] A study commissioned by the American Jewish Committee in 2021 came to the conclusion that antisemitism belongs to the "programmatic core" of the AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] According to the study, the party conducts "targeted campaigns" against Jewish celebrities.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The study's author, Lars Rensmann, stated that "despite some lip service to the contrary, hostility towards Israel, Holocaust relativization, antisemitic conspiracy thinking and anti-Jewish images occupy a prominent place" in AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD supports a ban on kosher slaughter within the country, as well as the "import and sale of kosher meat".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD instead wants to require the stunning of animals before slaughter which is against both Jewish and Muslim religious law that both require animals to be conscious when their necks are cut.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD describes German national identity as under threat both from European integration and from the presence and accommodation of immigrants and refugees within Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Former leader Petry said in March 2016: "I'm not against immigration, but ... the economic and social consequences of migration on both home and host countries are equally momentous ....
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The immigration of so many Muslims will change our culture.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] If this change is desired, it must be the product of a democratic decision supported by a broad majority.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In its programme, AfD wants to end what it describes as mass immigration and focus on taking in small numbers of skilled immigrants who are expected to integrate into society and speak German.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] It encourages German nationals to have more children, as opposed to trying to boost the German population through foreign migration.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party wants to review EU freedom of movement rules and states that immigrants must be employed and contribute to social security through paying taxes for at least four years before being allowed to receive state benefits.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD calls for mass deportations of foreign born criminals with multiple citizenship or permanent residency.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party describes the Geneva Convention on Refugees as "outdated", calls for stricter vetting of refugees, and believes the German government should invest in special economic and safe zones in third world nations as opposed to taking in large numbers of asylum seekers without background checks.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD is critical of multiculturalism in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party favours banning the burqa, the Islamic call to prayer in public areas and the construction of new minarets, ending foreign funding of mosques and putting imams through a state vetting procedure.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD began to employ anti-Muslim rhetoric during the leadership of Petry, who responded positively to comparisons between the party and Pegida.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2016 the party adopted several anti-Muslim positions and stated in its manifesto that "Islam does not belong to Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In January 2025 the Karlsruhe branch of the AfD initiated a controversial campaign by distributing flyers resembling flight tickets labeled *"Abschiebetickets"* ("deportation tickets") in mailboxes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] These flyers included a QR code linking to AfD Karlsruhe's website and were intended as promotional material for the upcoming Bundestag elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The action prompted investigations by the criminal police on suspicions of incitement to hatred (*Volksverhetzung*).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In January 2025, after a deadly knife attack perpetrated by an Afghan migrant, who had no residence permit, the CDU issued a motion regarding migration into the federal parliament, which attained a majority due to the AfD voting alongside the CDU.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] With this motion, CDU leader Friedrich Merz ignored his own proposal, uttered in November 2024, to only put questions to the vote that would find a majority without the AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The Bundestag went on to reject the CDU's proposed legislation a few days later, largely due to a dozen CDU legislators abstaining, a decision seen to be sparked by the AfD-related controversy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] According to its interim electoral manifesto, AfD opposes same-sex marriage and favours civil unions.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD deputy leader Beatrix von Storch has publicly opposed same-sex marriage.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In an effort to overturn same-sex marriage laws, AfD filed a lawsuit over the issue in 2017.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Hans-Christoph Berndt, the AfD's lead candidate for the 2024 Brandenburg state election, announced that, if elected, he would ban the practice of displaying rainbow flags on public buildings in the state.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD parliamentary group of the Landtag of Lower Saxony also introduced a motion to ban rainbow flags from public buildings in 2024.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD supports a ban on circumcision for non-medical reasons for those under the age of majority, saying that the practice constituted "serious violations of fundamental rights".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Alternative for Germany is an anti-abortion party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD has described its position as "pro-life" and rejects any state support for abortion.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The left-leaning newspaper *Die Tageszeitung* described the party as advocating "old gender roles".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Wolfgang Gedeon, an elected AfD representative, has included feminism, along with "sexualism" and "migrationism", in an ideology he calls "green communism" that he opposes, and argues for family values as part of German identity.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] As AfD has campaigned for traditional roles for women, it has aligned itself with groups opposed to modern feminism.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The youth wing of the party has used social media to campaign against aspects of modern feminism, with the support of party leadership.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Despite the 2015 split of economic liberals, AfD can still be broadly characterized as neoliberal on economic terms, emphasizing deregulation and much limited state intervention.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Attempts by some party factions to emphasize small and medium-sized enterprises, and advocate protectionism over free trade, have not had much success.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has a platform of climate change denial.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD accepts that the climate is changing, however, it denies that this change is attributable to human influences.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Instead the party argues that climate change is entirely caused by natural factors.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD argues that the rising carbon dioxide concentrations have been beneficial (contributed to a "greening" of Earth).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Next to its climate change denial, AfD opposes far-reaching climate policies: The party opposes energy transformation policies (*Energiewende*), wants to scrap the German Renewable Energy Act, the German Energy Saving Regulations, and the German Renewable Energy Heat Act.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] They also want to end bioenergy subsidies and restrict "uncontrolled expansion of wind energy".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party rejects the European Green Deal and has warned against the deindustrialization of Europe.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party argues that the energy transition threatens energy security, possibly leading to energy blackouts.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] It, therefore, views lignite as the only native energy source that can guarantee German energy security and energy self-sufficiency.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Furthermore, AfD wants to reinstate Germany's nuclear plants, arguing that closures between 2002 and 2011 were "economically damaging and not objectively justified".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party argues that the government should "allow a lifetime extension of still operating nuclear power plants on a transitional basis".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD wants a reinstatement of conscription in Germany, starting for able-bodied men at the age of 18.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] While AfD had been pro-NATO and pro-United States during the first Trump administration, it had been sharply critical of the Biden administration.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] It was significantly divided on whether to support Russia, but has since moved to a pro-Russian direction, opposing sanctions on Russia supported by NATO and the United States and calling for an end to military aid to Ukraine.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] It is also divided on free-trade agreements.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In March 2019, party leader Alexander Gauland said in an interview with the Russian newspaper *Komsomolskaya Pravda* that they consider the war in Donbas to be a Ukrainian internal matter, and that Germany should not get involved in the internal affairs of Ukraine or Russia.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] He also said AfD is against international sanctions on Russia.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD members have called for a more independent stance from the United States.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party has also endorsed accusations that the United States was involved in the 2022 Nord Stream pipeline sabotage.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has also called NATO's anti-Russian stance overly ideological and detrimental to Germany's interests.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] A large number of AfD delegates boycotted Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy in June 2024 when he gave a speech to the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2025, some high-ranking AfD members criticised Chrupalla's pro-Moscow position on foreign policy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] These include organizing street protests against NATO, bringing European delegations to Moscow and Crimea, and targeting "national parliaments of the EU" with resolutions to end EU sanctions on Russia and to grant recognition to Russia's annexation of Crimea.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Internal emails, including some from Mirzakhanyan, document substantial payments to EU politicians made in exchange for pro-Kremlin motions in their home countries, and to Manuel Ochsenreiter for publishing pro-Russian propaganda in his *Zuerst!* magazine.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In August 2023 a journalist investigation was published by *The Insider*, describing how money was funnelled from Moscow to AfD politicians who initiated a constitutional complaint in Germany against the supplies of weapons for Ukraine.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD supported peace negotiations on the Russo-Ukrainian War with the participation of Russia.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In October 2025 Georg Maier, the Interior Minister of Thuringia, raised concerns that the AfD might be using parliamentary inquiries to obtain information on critical infrastructure on behalf of the Kremlin.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] This includes detailed requests on transport and digital infrastructure, as well as water and energy supply, military capabilities, weak points and logistics.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD initially held a position of soft Euroscepticism by opposing the euro currency and eurozone bailouts, which the party saw as undermining European integration, but it was otherwise supportive of German membership of the European Union (EU).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] During the 2021 party conference in Dresden, a majority of AfD members voted to include more hardline policies against the European Union including German withdrawal from the bloc in the party's manifesto ahead of the 2021 German federal election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Since 2025 the AfD has been working with Hungary's nationalist prime minister, Viktor Orbán.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Alice Weidel praised Hungary as a model for AfD, saying that AfD shares Hungary's opposition to illegal immigration and stance on the European Union.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2025 Weidel stated about AfD's policy towards the European Union: "We should work together to reform the European Union at all costs.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party had previously been pro-Israel.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD supported the decision of US president Donald Trump to recognize Jerusalem as Israel's capital, as stated by AfD's Petr Bystron.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Despite AfD's pro-Israel stance, Israel has boycotted the party and has refused to hold ties with AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Following the October 7 attacks, the party supported cuts in German aid to Palestine via the UNRWA.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2024, AfD reversed its previously pro-Israel position, with co-leader Tino Chrupalla calling for an end to Germany's current relationship with Israel, which Chrupalla described as "one-sided", as well as an end to arms exports to Israel during the Gaza war.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] This decision drew criticism from some other members of the AfD parliamentary group, suggesting a continued internal divide on the issue.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Chrupalla criticised the German government's support for Israel during the war and rejected "blanket" Islamophobia.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Some AfD members referred to Israel's conduct as constituting genocide in Gaza.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Nevertheless, in January 2025, the other co-leader, Alice Weidel, affirmed her support for Israel, but noted that she "didn't know how she would solve this conflict".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Chrupalla and Weidel have been described as divided on the issue of Israel, with Weidel continuing to affirm German support for Israel's right to self-defence.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] At the start of the Twelve-Day War between Israel and Iran in June 2025, AfD foreign policy spokesperson Markus Frohnmaier expressed support for a diplomatic solution and called on both sides to cease hostilities, while insisting that Iran should not pursue a nuclear weapons programme.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2018 and 2019, AfD Bundestag members visited Ba'athist Syria, meeting with senior officials from the government of Bashar al-Assad and advocating for the return of Syrian refugees.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2026, in the midst of the 2026 Iran war, party leader Tino Chrupalla praised Spain's refusal to allow American forces to use its military bases for the conflict, and urged Germany to follow Spain's example.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] He further proposed ending the stationing of US forces in Germany, as well as their nuclear weapons presence in the country.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party had previously demanded the German government to strip the "developing country" status for China, voicing opposition to "Chinese economic espionage" and opposing Chinese state-owned company COSCO Shipping buying of a stake in the Port of Hamburg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] However, it started changing its position in 2023, with AfD's Bundestag caucus accusing foreign minister Annalena Baerbock and economic affairs minister Robert Habeck of launching an "economic war" against China.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has also criticised restrictions on the use of 5G material from Chinese companies Huawei and ZTE.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD leader Tino Chrupalla has also voiced opposition to restrictions on Chinese technology and backed Chinese foreign minister Qin Gang on his peace-brokering efforts for Russia's invasion of Ukraine.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD currently calls for closer economic, cultural and scientific relations with China.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Nevertheless, in their manifesto for the 2025 federal election, AfD has also called for limits in the involvement of Chinese companies in Germany's seaports and digital infrastructure.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] It is also opposed to further development aid, including those that would benefit climate change programs or Chinese students in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] After joining the parliament with more than 90 representatives in the 2017 federal election, the party received more than 70 million euros per year; this probably rose to more than 100 million euros per year from 2019 onward.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party has also established and acknowledged a foundation for political education, and other purposes, close to the party but organized separately, which may be able to claim up to 80 million euros per year.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] This foundation would need to be acknowledged by the federal parliament in Germany first, but it has a legal claim to these subsidies.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2018 the Alternative for Germany donation scandal became public, as federal and European Parliament politicians Alice Weidel, Jörg Meuthen, Marcus Pretzell, and Guido Reil had profited from illegal and unnamed donations from non-EU countries.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The acceptance of donations from non-EU countries is prohibited for German parties and politicians.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Young Alternative for Germany (German: *Junge Alternative für Deutschland*, JA) was founded in 2013 as the youth organisation of AfD, while remaining legally independent from its mother party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In view of JA's independence, it has been regarded by some in AfD's hierarchy as being somewhat wayward, with JA repeatedly accused of being "too far-right", politically regressive and antifeminist by the German mainstream media.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In December 2024 the main party of the AfD announced its intention to cut ties with the JA in connection to its classification by the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD leadership are planning to found a new organisation as its youth wing.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] On 12 January 2025, AfD leadership voted to formally replace the JA as its youth organisation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Following the 2014 European Parliament election on 12 June, AfD was accepted into the European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR) group in the European Parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2016, AfD announced a closer cooperation with the right-wing populist party Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ), which was a member of the Europe of Nations and Freedom (ENF) group.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] On 8 March 2016, the bureau of the ECR group began motions to exclude AfD MEPs from their group due to the party's links with the far-right FPÖ and controversial remarks by two party leaders about shooting immigrants.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] MEP Beatrix von Storch pre-empted her imminent expulsion by leaving the ECR group to join the Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy group on 8 April, and Marcus Pretzell was expelled from the ECR group on 12 April 2016.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] During the party convention on 30 April 2016, Pretzell announced his intention to join the Europe of Nations and Freedom group, although he subsequently left AfD to join Petry's Blue Party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In April 2019, Jörg Meuthen appeared alongside Northern League leader Matteo Salvini, National Rally leader Marine Le Pen, and politicians from the Danish People's Party and FPÖ to announce the formation of a new European political alliance.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD later joined this group in the European Parliament, which was ultimately named the Identity and Democracy group.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In July 2023, the AfD joined the Identity and Democracy Party, the European political party affiliated with this group.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD initially maintained close cooperation with the French National Rally and Marine Le Pen.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2024, it was reported that the relations between the two parties had become strained after AfD spokesmen attended the 2023 Potsdam far-right meeting.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In response, the AfD's leadership held a meeting with Le Pen and denied endorsing the words of some of the people at the meeting.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The Flemish Vlaams Belang criticised Krah's words as "increasingly problematic" but declined to immediately expel the AfD faction, stating they preferred to review the situation after the election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The Estonian EKRE and the FPÖ supported expelling Krah but opposed the expulsion of AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] After an internal meeting and vote, the Identity and Democracy board subsequently agreed to expel AfD, with group leader Marco Zanni citing Krah's interview, as well as allegations of Chinese and Russian espionage influence on AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party consequently moved to non-inscrits.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Following the decision, AfD said they would negotiate to rejoin the group and announced Krah would not sit with the AfD faction in the European Parliament after the election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Following the 2024 European Parliament election, the AfD began negotiations with several of these parties to form a new European Parliament group.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Although the AfD originally negotiated with S.O.S.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Romania, it later rejected S.O.S.'s attempt to join the group.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The KKP was also eventually rejected from the group.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Despite the Czech SPD's prior declaration that it would not sit with the AfD, and past opposition by Poland's New Hope to cooperation with the AfD, both parties ultimately joined the AfD-led Europe of Sovereign Nations group.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In August 2024, AfD also formed the Europe of Sovereign Nations party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In the United States, AfD has connections with former Department of Government Efficiency leader Elon Musk and groups associated with the Republican Party, particularly the Young Republicans.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In response to the German domestic intelligence agency 2025 classification of the party as a "confirmed right-wing extremist endeavor" permitting monitoring of it, US Vice President JD Vance wrote, "The West tore down the Berlin Wall together.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] And it has been rebuilt – not by the Soviets or the Russians, but by the German establishment." US secretary of state Marco Rubio also wrote "Germany just gave its spy agency new powers to surveil the opposition.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has contacts with the People's Party of Canada through the AfD MEP Christine Anderson.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The former President of Switzerland, Ueli Maurer of the Swiss People's Party, has endorsed the 2025 AfD election campaign and addressed AfD events.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2025, Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán and Weidel announced the start of cooperation between AfD and Fidesz.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] During its 2025 German federal election campaign, the AfD also received support from the Spanish Vox party and the Alliance of Independent Social Democrats in Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has some links with the UK Homeland Party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] At the outset, AfD presented itself as conservative and middle-class, catering to a well-educated demographic; around two-thirds of supporters listed on its website in the early days held doctorates, leading to AfD being nicknamed the "professors' party" in its early days.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party was described as professors and academics who dislike the compromises inflicted on their purist theories by German party politics.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] 86% of the party's initial supporters were male.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Outside the Berlin hotel where the party held its inaugural meeting, it has been alleged that copies of *Junge Freiheit*, a weekly that is also popular with the far right, were being handed out.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The *Rheinische Post* pointed out that some AfD members and supporters write for the conservative paper.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] There was also a protest outside the venue of the party's inaugural meeting by Andreas Storr, a National Democratic Party of Germany (NPD) representative in the Landtag of Saxony, as the NPD sees AfD as a rival for Eurosceptic votes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2013, AfD party organizers sent out the message that they are not trying to attract right-wing radicals and toned down rhetoric on their Facebook page following media allegations that it too closely evoked the language of the far right.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] At that time, AfD checked applicants for membership to exclude far-right and former NPD members who support the anti-euro policy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The former party chairman Bernd Lucke stated that "[t]he applause is coming from the wrong side", regarding praise his party gained from the NPD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Members of Alliance 90/Green Party have accused AfD of pandering to xenophobic and nationalistic sentiments.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] There have been altercations between AfD members and Green Youth members.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Following the 2013 federal election, the anti-Islam German Freedom Party unilaterally pledged to support AfD in the 2014 elections and concentrate its efforts on local elections only.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Bernd Lucke responded by saying that the German Freedom Party's support was unwanted and sent a letter to AfD party associations recommending a hiring freeze.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2018 Tino Chrupalla, the current co-leader of AfD, gave an interview to holocaust denier, antisemite and right-wing extremist Nikolai Nerling, which was uploaded to YouTube.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] It was staged as having occurred by chance, but an earlier shot in the video reveals Chrupalla waiting in the background.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] As such, the interview was cited in the 2019 Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution report on AfD as evidence of the party's "Connections to the framework of a so-called new right or right-wing populist 'resistance milieu'".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] On 24 June 2024 it was announced that two parliamentary groups consisting of members of the AfD and Die Heimat formerly the NPD, had been formed in the Brandenburg town of Lauchhammer and the district of Oberspreewald-Lausitz.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In Lauchhammer, the joint parliamentary group will be represented in the town council under the name "AfDplus", while the "Heimat & Zukunft" parliamentary group has been formed in the district council of Oberspreewald-Lausitz.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Thomas Gürtler from *Die Heimat* will play a leading role in both bodies.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] This development is seen as the first official coalition between AfD and the far-right party *Die Heimat*.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The formation of the parliamentary groups was supported by statements made by AfD chairman Tino Chrupalla, who emphasised that there would be no "firewalls" to other parties at local level.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2016 AfD MEP Marcus Pretzell was expelled from the party after he said that German borders should be defended from incursion by refugees "with armed force as a measure of last resort".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Petry later stated that no policeman "wants to fire on a refugee and I don't want that either" but that border police must follow the law to maintain the integrity of European borders.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Afterwards, Petry made several attempts to justify these statements.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In response to the Pegida movement and demonstrations, members of AfD have expressed different opinions of it, with Lucke describing the movement as "a sign that these people do not feel their concerns are understood by politicians".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In response to the CDU Interior Minister Thomas de Maizière alleging an "overlap" between Pegida rallies and AfD, Alexander Gauland stated that AfD are "natural allies of this movement".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Hans-Olaf Henkel asked members of the party not to join the demonstrations, telling *Der Tagesspiegel* that he believed it could not be ruled out that they had "xenophobic or even racist connotations".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] A straw poll by *The Economist* found that nine out of ten Pegida protesters would back the AfD.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The speech was widely criticised as antisemitic or neo-Nazi, among others by Jewish leaders in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Within AfD, he was described by his party chairwoman, Frauke Petry, as a "burden to the party", while other members of the party, such as Alexander Gauland, said that they found no antisemitism in the speech.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2017, AfD leaders asked for Höcke to be expelled from the party due to his speech.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The arbitration committee of AfD in Thuringia was set to rule on the leaders' request.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In May 2018, an AfD tribunal ruled that Höcke was allowed to stay in the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD politician Matthias Helferich had described himself in social media messages as the "friendly face of the ns [*sic*]," referring to National Socialism.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Helferich also called himself a "democratic Freisler," referring to a Nazi-era judge.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The event triggered the 2024 German anti-extremism protests.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In May 2024, Höcke was convicted and fined €13,000 by the state court in Halle for deliberately using a banned slogan *"Alles für Deutschland"*, associated with the Nazi Party's paramilitary wing, in a May 2021 campaign speech.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] In the same month, the party member Maximilian Krah defence of the *Waffen-SS* caused controversy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Following the 2025 federal election it was confirmed that Maximillian Krah and Matthias Helferich would be joining the parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] On 2 May 2025 the German domestic intelligence agency, Bundesamt für Verfassungsschutz (BfV), published a report spanning 1,100 pages which sought to assess whether the AfD should be designated as an 'extremist' group.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Central to its thesis was the party's anti-Muslim stance, and it favouring national and ethnic Germans over migrants.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD denounced its designation as a politically motivated attempt to discredit and criminalize it.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The designation opens the possibility of civil servants belonging to the AfD facing dismissal depending on their role within the entity, according to the country's interior ministry.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD members and activists were listed as keeping close ties with Russian politicians and receiving financial benefits in an OCCRP investigation of Russia's International Agency for Current Policy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD Politicians Eugen Schmidt, Olga Petersen, and Ulrich Oehme founded the "Association for the Prevention of Discrimination and Exclusion of Russian-Germans and Russian-speaking Fellow Citizens in Germany" (Vadar e.V.) in June 2022.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The association attests that Germany has an "anti-Russian mood" and wants to offer legal help to "Russian-Germans and Russian-speaking fellow citizens" who would be discriminated against or excluded by the war of aggression.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The association says it financed the legal representation of pro-Russian influencer Alina Lipp and is opposed to the German ban on the Russian military and propaganda symbol *Z*.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] The association denies Russian war crimes in the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] According to a report in the *Sächsische Zeitung*, Vadar shares a bank account with an institution that is majority Russian-owned.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] According to German public broadcaster ARD, German security authorities are investigating the association connections to Russian authorities.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/alternative-for-germany-p02] Internal emails, including some from Mirzakhanyan, document substantial payments to EU politicians made in exchange for pro-Kremlin motions in their home countries, and to journalist and AfD member Manuel Ochsenreiter for publishing pro-Russian propaganda in his *Zuerst!* magazine.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In February 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer announced that she would resign her position as CDU leader later in the year and would not put herself forward as a candidate for chancellor for the 2021 federal election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was succeeded by Armin Laschet at the January 2021 CDU leadership election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer previously served as secretary general of the party and as Minister President of Saarland from 2011 to 2018, the first woman to lead the Government of Saarland and fourth woman to head a German state government.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer is regarded as socially conservative, but on the CDU's left wing in economic policy and has been described as a centrist.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is an active Catholic and has served on the Central Committee of German Catholics.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is the second woman to hold the office of German defence minister.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was succeeded by Christine Lambrecht.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In October 2021 she proposed for the use of nuclear weapons against Russia via a First-Strike capability as a deterrence against any "provocation" or aggression.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She renounced her Bundestag mandate and retired from politics after the 2021 federal election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Annegret Kramp was born on 9 August 1962 in Völklingen, located on the Saar River midway between Saarlouis and Saarbrücken, around 40 kilometres from Luxembourg and close to the border with France.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She grew up in the neighbouring town of Püttlingen.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Her father was a special education teacher and a headmaster.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She graduated from high school in 1982 and considered becoming a school teacher, but decided to study politics and law at the University of Trier and at Saarland University, where she earned a master's degree in 1990.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer joined the CDU while still in high school in 1981.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 1984 she was elected to the district council of Püttlingen, and in 1985 became chairwoman of the city's CDU association.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] From 1985 to 1988 she was also a member of the regional board of the Young Union in Saarland.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] From 1991 to 1998 she served as a policy and planning officer for the CDU in Saarland under environment minister Klaus Töpfer.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 1998, Kramp-Karrenbauer replaced Töpfer in the federal Bundestag, serving seven months before losing re-election in the SPD landslide the same year.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 1999, she was an advisor to Peter Müller, then chairman of the CDU parliamentary group in the Landtag of Saarland and later Minister-President.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] That same year she became a chairwoman of the Women's Union.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was elected to the Landtag of Saarland in 1999.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She served as Minister of the Interior in the government of Peter Müller; the first woman to hold that office in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She took on more responsibilities in 2004, and changed roles in 2007 following a cabinet reshuffle, becoming Minister of Education and again in 2009, becoming Minister of Labor in the so-called Jamaica coalition government.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2008, she was elected chairwoman of the *Kultusministerkonferenz*.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Throughout her time in state government, she also served at various times as minister responsible for women, sports, family, and culture.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the negotiations to form a coalition government following the 2009 federal election, Kramp-Karrenbauer was part of the CDU–CSU delegation in the working group on education and research policy, led by Annette Schavan and Andreas Pinkwart.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Shortly afterwards, she ended the coalition and triggered an election, blaming the party for "dismantling itself" and arguing that the three-party coalition had lost the necessary "trust, stability, and capacity to act".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Under Kramp-Karrenbauer's leadership, the CDU won 40.7% of the vote in the 2017 state elections, up from 35.2% in 2012.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] While serving as Minister-President, Kramp-Karrenbauer, who speaks French, was also Commissioner of the Federal Republic of Germany for Cultural Affairs under the Treaty on Franco-German Cooperation between 2011 and 2014.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She continued to be a member of the German-French Friendship Group that was set up by the upper chambers of the German and French national parliaments, respectively the Bundesrat and the Senate.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Furthermore, as one of the state's representatives at the federal Bundesrat, she served on the Committee on Cultural Affairs, the Committee on Foreign Affairs, and the Committee on Defence.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was a CDU delegate to the Federal Convention to elect the president of Germany in 2012 and in 2017.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was also for a short time part of the CDU–CSU delegation's leadership team in the negotiations to form a "grand coalition" following the 2013 federal elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She again played a role in the negotiations to form a fourth coalition government under Chancellor Angela Merkel in 2018, leading a working group on education policy alongside Stefan Müller, Manuela Schwesig and Hubertus Heil.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As Minister-President of Saarland, Kramp-Karrenbauer promoted the French language, aiming to make the state fully bilingual in German and French and thus promote Saarland as a bicultural European region similar to neighbouring Luxembourg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] While Saarland had rejoined Germany five years before Kramp-Karrenbauer's birth when a majority voted against becoming an independent state, it has a long history of association with France dating back to the late 18th century.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In February 2018, Merkel nominated Kramp-Karrenbauer as the new secretary general of the CDU.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was confirmed at the CDU party conference on 26 February, securing 98.87% of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As secretary general, she managed the party and oversaw its election campaigns.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She also embarked on a major listening tour of the country, holding more than 40 meetings with local CDU associations and working on a new political manifesto for the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In October 2018, following bad results for the CDU/CSU in state elections in Bavaria and Hesse, Chancellor Merkel announced she would not stand for re-election as party leader in the CDU convention at the end of the year, triggering a leadership election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Former Bundestag leader of the CDU and businessman Friedrich Merz jumped into the race immediately while Health Minister Jens Spahn and Kramp-Karrenbauer announced their bids shortly after.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was perceived to be Merkel's chosen heir and a continuation of her style and centrist ideology while Merz was an old rival from Merkel's early days as party leader and was very open about his intention to move the party in a more conservative direction.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Nevertheless, the Chancellor did not state her preferences.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As the vote approached, opinion polls showed that Kramp-Karrenbauer was favoured by CDU voters and the general public alike.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The contest was held on 7 December and after coming out on top in the first round, Kramp-Karrenbauer narrowly defeated Merz in a run-off, becoming the new leader of the CDU.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the immediate aftermath of her election, surveys showed an increase in the CDU's vote share; however, it was short-lived.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the first months of her tenure, there were a series of gaffes and according to the press a failure to connect with voters.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the run-up to the 2019 European Parliament election, which was seen as her first major electoral test, the CDU's campaign was embroiled by a row between the party and YouTube personality Rezo.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] It was caused by a viral YouTube video posted by Rezo in which he called out the parties of the governing Grand Coalition (CDU/CSU and SPD) and urged viewers not to vote for them.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer reacted, stating that the electoral law should be changed to prevent social media personalities like Rezo from influencing the voters' choice in the midst of a campaign.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The statement was harshly criticized as an attack on freedom of expression and damaged the image of Kramp-Karrenbauer among young people.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Shortly afterwards, a Bloomberg report stated that Chancellor Merkel thought that her successor was not up to the job, further hindering her popularity.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The European Elections resulted in the CDU's worst national showing ever, below 30%.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] After the underwhelming result, rumors emerged that some CDU politicians planned to shun Kramp-Karrenbauer and put up another Chancellor candidate for the next Bundestag election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer announced her resignation as leader of the CDU on 10 February 2020 as a result of the 2020 Thuringian government crisis.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The plan was that she would resign in the summer and her successor would be elected, but this was postponed to December due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] When Ursula von der Leyen was elected President of the European Commission in July 2019, Kramp-Karrenbauer succeeded her as Federal Minister of Defence in the government of Chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] This was the first time that she held a position in the federal government.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] For the 2021 elections, Kramp-Karrenbauer was later elected to lead the CDU campaign in Saarland.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Shortly after having been elected, she announced her decision to step down from the parliament and instead make room for Markus Uhl who had failed to secure a seat.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In mid-2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer oversaw the German military's withdrawal from Afghanistan after almost two decades.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In July 2021, she sent the frigate *Bayern* off on a seven-month voyage that will take it to Australia, Japan, South Korea and Vietnam, making it the first German warship to pass through the South China Sea since 2002.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] During her time in office, Kramp-Karrenbauer publicly apologized to soldiers who for decades faced discrimination, discharge or convictions on the basis of their sexual orientation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2021, she successfully introduced legislation to rehabilitate those soldiers.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer disbanded a company of the Special Forces Command (KSK) after police seized weapons and ammunition during a raid on the property of a KSK soldier.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She later resisted calls for KSK to be disbanded altogether and instead pushed through the unit's reform.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In June 2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer recalled 30 German soldiers from service at the NATO Enhanced Forward Presence in Lithuania, with ringleaders facing immediate dismissal, after an article in *Der Spiegel* accused them of making racist and anti-Semitic remarks and of sexual violence.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Also in 2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer opened the Bundeswehr's first-ever Air and Space Operations Centre (ASOC) in Uedem, expanding Germany's existing space situation center into the new structure.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] During Kramp-Karrenbauer's tenure as Minister-President of Saarland, she had consistently high approval ratings in the low to mid-70's among her constituents.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was the most popular politician in Saarland according to Infratest dimap from November 2010 until her departure as Minister-President.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was considered one of the most popular state government leaders nationwide.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] When entering federal politics, Kramp-Karrenbauer had a positive net approval rating from her election as CDU General Secretary in February 2018 until March 2019, just shortly after having been elected as Leader of the Christian Democratic Union.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Her nationwide popularity peaked in January 2019, when she had a net approval of +17% and was seen as second-most popular politician overall.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] There was then a sharp decline in her popularity following gaffes and electoral defeats for the Christian Democrats in several elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As of February 2020, she is one of the least popular German politicians.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] From 2024 to 2025, Kramp-Karrenbauer chaired an independent expert commission convened by the Global Perspectives Initiative to develop recommendations for Germany's development policy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Since 2026, Kramp-Karrenbauer has been serving as chair of the Konrad Adenauer Foundation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer is perceived as a moderate or centrist Christian Democrat.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She has been described as socially conservative, but on the CDU's left wing in economic policy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is regarded as more conservative than Angela Merkel.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Nevertheless, in the German press, her often used nickname during her party leadership was "Mini-Merkel", reflecting both her size and her political views.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer opposes same sex marriage, having compared it to incest and polygamy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Amid her party's campaign for the 2013 federal elections, Kramp-Karrenbauer suggested Germany return to a top income tax rate of more than 53%, setting off a fierce debate in her party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In her view, Merkel's predecessor Gerhard Schröder had gone too far in reducing the top rate from 53% to 42% in the 1990s.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In May 2014, she was among leading members of Merkel's CDU who called for reductions to offset fiscal drag—the automatic increases in the tax-take that occur as inflation and income growth push wage-earners further into their marginal higher tax-bracket.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] When the Federal Constitutional Court ruled in favour of tax equality for same-sex couples in 2013, Kramp-Karrenbauer voiced her concerns about also granting full adoption rights for same-sex couples, stating: "The traditional family unit is the core of not only Germany but all nations".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2015, she caused a public controversy by arguing that "if we open up [the definition of marriage] to become a long-term responsible partnership between two adults, then other demands can't be ruled out, such as a marriage between close relatives or between more than two people".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] For the 2021 national elections, Kramp-Karrenbauer endorsed Armin Laschet as the Christian Democrats' joint candidate to succeed Chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer criticised the German-supported Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline that would allow Germany to effectively double the amount of gas it imports from Russia, saying that Nord Stream 2 "is not just an economic project but a political one".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Ambassador to Germany Richard Grenell sent letters to German companies involved in the construction of Nord Stream 2, threatening CAATSA sanctions.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer has supported arms exports to Saudi Arabia, which has been waging war in Yemen and was condemned for massive human rights violations.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In late 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer proposed that the European Union should try again to reach a trade agreement with the United States after the elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In October 2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer had talked about the possibility of deploying nuclear arms against Russia.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer supports stricter immigration policies.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer supported Angela Merkel's refugee policies and her decision to let migrants into Germany in 2015–2016, many fleeing wars in the Middle East, but demanded more toughness in some cases.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] At the beginning of 2016, she declared herself against a unilateral closure of German borders, since she feared a break-up of the European Union.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Furthermore, instead of carrying out deportations with commercial airplanes, she said it may be necessary to use their separate aircraft.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She demanded in November 2018 that after expulsion offenders must be refused re-entry for life, not only to Germany but also throughout the Schengen area, and cited the 2018 gang rape in Freiburg as an example.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is married to Helmut Karrenbauer, a retired mining engineer, with whom she has three children, born in 1988, 1991 and 1998; they live in the city of Püttlingen.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer is an avid reader and speaks French.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Modern Baden-Württemberg includes the historical territories of Baden, Prussian Hohenzollern, and Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg became a state of West Germany in April 1952 through the merger of South Baden, Württemberg-Baden, and Württemberg-Hohenzollern.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] These states had been created by the Allies as they separated traditional states into occupation zones after World War II.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg is especially known for its strong economy with various industries like car manufacturing, electrical engineering, mechanical engineering, the service sector, and more.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Ranking third among the German states by gross regional product (GRP) and first by research and development spending, Baden-Württemberg is considered one of the most prosperous and innovative regions in Europe.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Part of the Four Motors for Europe and located in the Blue Banana, some of the largest German companies are headquartered in Baden-Württemberg, including Mercedes-Benz Group, Schwarz Group, Porsche, Bosch and SAP.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The sobriquet *Ländle*, a diminutive of the word *Land* in the local Swabian, Alemannic and Franconian dialects, is sometimes used as a synonym for Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg is formed from the historical territories of Württemberg, Baden and Prussian Hohenzollern.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden spans along the flat right bank of the river Rhine from north-west to the south (Lake Constance) of the present state, whereas Württemberg and Hohenzollern lie more inland and hillier, including areas such as the Swabian Jura mountain range.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The Black Forest formed part of the border between Baden and Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In 100 AD, the Roman Empire invaded and occupied Württemberg, constructing a limes along its northern borders.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Over the course of the third century AD, the Alemanni forced the Romans to retreat west beyond the Rhine and Danube rivers.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In 496 AD the Alemanni were defeated by a Frankish invasion led by Clovis I.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The Holy Roman Empire was later established.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The majority of people in this region continued to be Roman Catholics, even after the Protestant Reformation influenced populations in northern Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In the late 18th and early 19th century, Künzelsau, the capital of the Hohenlohe district, became the centre of emigration to the UK of pork butchers and bacon factors.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The pioneers noticed a niche for speciality pork products in the rapidly growing English cities, especially those in the industrial centre and North.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Many married local women and sent word home that a good living could be made in England; others followed.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, numerous people emigrated from this primarily rural area to the United States for economic reasons.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] At the beginning of the 20th century, the territory of modern-day Baden-Württemberg consisted of the Grand Duchy of Baden, the Kingdom of Württemberg and the province of Hohenzollern of the Kingdom of Prussia.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Since 1871, these had been part of the German Empire.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In the aftermath of World War I and as part of the German revolution of 1918, the monarchs of Baden, Württemberg and Prussia were deposed, and these states became democratic republics: the Republic of Baden, the Free People's State of Württemberg and the Free State of Prussia.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Following Adolf Hitler becoming chancellor of Germany in 1933, the democratic institutions of Baden, Württemberg and Prussia were abolished as part of the *Gleichschaltung*.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] After World War II, the Allies established three states in the territory of modern-day Baden-Württemberg: (South) Baden, Württemberg-Baden and Württemberg-Hohenzollern.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden and Württemberg-Hohenzollern were occupied by France, while Württemberg-Baden was occupied by the United States.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The new artificial borders were a consequence of France requesting its own occupation zone in Germany after World War II, and the Americans' wish to keep the A8 motorway, which spans east-west across northern Baden and northern Württemberg, wholly within their occupation zone.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In 1949, each state became a founding member of the Federal Republic of Germany (West Germany), with Article 118 of the German constitution providing an accession procedure.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] On 9 December 1951, a referendum was held in Württemberg-Baden, Württemberg-Hohenzollern and (South) Baden over a possible merger, or the restoration of the former pre-war states.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] There was strong support for the merger in Württemberg and Hohenzollern, but opposition in Baden.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] While a majority in the historic area of Baden (52%) voted to restore the former pre-war states, the majority of voters overall (69%) voted in favor of a merger.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg officially became a state on 25 April 1952.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] There were still opponents to the merger of Baden and Württemberg, however.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In 1956 the Federal Constitutional Court decided that the population of Baden should have their say in a separate referendum.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The second referendum was delayed, however, and the Federal Constitutional Court decided in 1969 that another referendum should be held by 30 June 1970.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The referendum in the historic area of Baden was finally held on 7 June 1970, with 81.9% of the voters voting in favour of the merger of Baden and Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg shares borders with the German states of Rhineland-Palatinate, Hesse, and Bavaria, and also shares borders with France (Alsace, within the region of Grand Est), and Switzerland (cantons of Basel-Landschaft, Basel-Stadt, Aargau, Zürich, Schaffhausen and Thurgau).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Most of the major cities of Baden-Württemberg straddle the banks of the Neckar River, which has its source in Villingen-Schwenningen and runs downstream (from southwest to the centre, then northwest) through the state past Tübingen, Stuttgart, Heilbronn, Heidelberg, and Mannheim.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The Rhine (German: *Rhein*) forms the western border as well as large portions of the southern border.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The Black Forest (Schwarzwald), the central mountain range of the state, rises east of the Upper Rhine valley.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The high plateau of the Swabian Alb, between the Neckar, the Black Forest, and the Danube, is an essential European watershed.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg shares Lake Constance (Bodensee, also known regionally as the Swabian Sea) with Switzerland, Austria and Bavaria, the international borders within its waters not being clearly defined.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] It shares the foothills of the Alps (known as the Allgäu) with Bavaria and the Austrian Vorarlberg, but Baden-Württemberg itself has no mainland border with Austria.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The Danube is conventionally taken to be formed by the confluence of the two streams Brigach and Breg just east of Donaueschingen.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The source of the Donaubach, which flows into the Danube, in Donaueschingen is often referred to as the "source of the Danube" (*Donauquelle*).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Hydrologically, the source of the Danube is the source of the Breg as the larger of the two formative streams, which rises near Furtwangen.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The forests in this region are home to common pests such as *Melolontha Hippocastrani*, that cause damage to the foliage and soil.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg is–along with Bavaria–the southernmost part of Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] This is mostly due to a high amount of mountains and highlands inside of the state.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Most parts in the western parts (Baden) lower than 500–800 metres (1,600–2,600 ft) enjoy an almost year round mild oceanic climate (cfb in Köppen classification).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The climate in the eastern parts of the state is more continental.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] For instance, winters in the city of Ulm are colder than in Berlin.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] While winters in the warmest areas often lack snow, the Black Forest, Swabian Alb and the Alps tend to get snow frequently, especially in areas of high elevation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Summers here have more rain than in the valleys, but winters tend to have more sun.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Due to the differences of the landscapes, average annual temperatures reach from only 5 °C (41 °F) in the microclimates of Black Forest and Allgäu up to 13 °C (55 °F) in the Upper Rhine Valley.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg is divided into thirty-five districts (*Landkreise*) and nine independent cities (*Stadtkreise*), both grouped into the four Administrative Districts (*Regierungsbezirke*) of Freiburg, Karlsruhe, Stuttgart, and Tübingen.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The Baden-Württemberg General Auditing Office acts as an independent body to monitor public offices' correct use of public funds.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The state parliament of Baden-Württemberg is the *Landtag*, located in Stuttgart.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The state government is currently formed by a Greens-CDU coalition as the cabinet of Minister-President Cem Özdemir (Greens).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The politics of Baden-Württemberg have traditionally been dominated by the conservative Christian Democratic Union of Germany (CDU), which had led all but one government since 1952 until 2011.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In the *Landtag* elections held on 27 March 2011, voters replaced the Christian Democrats and centre-right Free Democrats (FDP) coalition with an alliance of the Greens and Social Democrats (SPD), which secured a four-seat majority in the state parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The alliance elected the Greens-led first Kretschmann cabinet under Winfried Kretschmann because the Greens had surprisingly won 36 seats, one more than the Social Democrats' 35 seats.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In the 2016 election, the popular Kretschmann and his Greens were reelected and, with their nationwide best result, turned out first place for the first time in any election in German history.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] However, because of the Social Democrats' heavy losses, the Greens formed a coalition government with the Christian Democrats, the second Kretschmann cabinet.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] After the elections in 2021 and 2026, the Greens-CDU coalition was upheld.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Although Baden-Württemberg has relatively few natural resources compared to other regions of Germany, the state is among the most prosperous and wealthiest regions in Europe, with a generally low unemployment rate historically.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The state's economic performance benefits from and relies on its well-developed infrastructure.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Apart from the city-states of Berlin, Bremen and Hamburg, Baden-Württemberg offers the fourth-shortest routes to trains and buses on average among all German states.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Despite it not being predominantly reliant upon an industrial capacity, Baden-Württemberg is one of the strongest economic states in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg also has the most employees (233,296) in the automotive industry of all German states as of 2018, as well as the third-highest number of motor vehicles of all German states (2020).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] If Baden-Württemberg were a sovereign country (2020), it would have an economy comparable to that of Sweden in terms of nominal gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Despite this, Baden-Württemberg's economy is dominated by small and medium-sized enterprises, like most companies in German-speaking countries are.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Although poor in workable natural resources (formerly lead, zinc, iron, silver, copper, and salts) and still very rural in some areas, the region is heavily industrialised overall.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In 2003, there were almost 8,800 manufacturing enterprises with more than 20 employees, but only 384 with more than 500.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] There are 3,779 companies in Baden-Württemberg corporate family which come to 1000–5000 employees in total.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The latter category accounts for 43% of the 1.2 million persons employed in the industry.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The *Mittelstand* or mid-sized company model is the backbone of the Baden-Württemberg economy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Medium-sized businesses and a tradition of branching into different industrial sectors have ensured specialisation over a wide range.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] A fifth of the "old" Federal Republic's industrial gross value added is generated by Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Turnover for manufacturing in 2003 exceeded 240,000 million, 43% of which came from exports.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The region depends to some extent on global economic developments, though the great adaptability of the region's economy has generally helped it through crises.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Half of the employees in the manufacturing industry are in mechanical and electrical engineering and automobile construction.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] This is also where the largest enterprises are to be found.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The importance of the precision mechanics industry also extends beyond the region's borders, as does that of the optical, clock making, toy, metallurgy and electronics industries.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The textile industry, which formerly dominated much of the region, has disappeared from Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Research and development (R&D) is funded jointly by the state and industry.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In 2001, more than a fifth of the 100,000 or so persons working in R&D in Germany were located in Baden-Württemberg, most of them in the Stuttgart area.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg is also the region with the highest GDP of the Four Motors for Europe.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] A study performed in 2007 by the neo-liberal thinktank Initiative for New Social Market Economy and the trade newspaper *Wirtschaftswoche* awarded Baden-Württemberg for being the "economically most successful and most dynamic state" among the 16 states.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The unemployment rate stood at 3% in October 2018 and was the second lowest in Germany behind only Bavaria and one of the lowest in the European Union.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg is a popular holiday destination.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Sites of former monasteries such as the ones on Reichenau Island and at Maulbronn (both World Heritage Sites) as well as Bebenhausen Abbey are to be found.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In spring and autumn (April/May and September/October), beer festivals (fun fairs) take place at the Cannstatter Wasen in Stuttgart.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The Cannstatter Volksfest, in the autumn, is the second-largest such festival in the world after the Munich Oktoberfest.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In late November and early December Christmas markets are a tourist magnet in all major towns, the largest being in Stuttgart during the three weeks before Christmas.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The Bertha Benz Memorial Route is a 194 km signposted scenic route from Mannheim via Heidelberg and Wiesloch to Pforzheim and back, which follows the route of the world's first long-distance journey by automobile which Bertha Benz undertook in August 1888.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg also is home to Europa-Park in Rust.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The largest theme park in Germany, and the second most popular theme park in Europe, after Disneyland Paris.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg is home to some of the oldest, most renowned, and prestigious universities in Germany, such as the universities of Heidelberg (founded in 1386, the oldest university within the territory of modern Germany), Freiburg (founded in 1457), and Tübingen (founded in 1477).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] It also contains three of the eleven German *excellence universities* (Heidelberg, Tübingen, Konstanz and Karlsruhe and formerly, Freiburg ).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Other university towns are Mannheim and Ulm.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Furthermore, two universities are located in the state capital Stuttgart, the University of Hohenheim, and the University of Stuttgart.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Ludwigsburg is home to the national film school Filmakademie Baden-Württemberg (Film Academy Baden-Wuerttemberg).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The private International University in Germany was situated in Bruchsal, but closed in 2009.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Another private university is located in Friedrichshafen, Zeppelin University.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Furthermore, there are more than a dozen *Fachhochschulen*, i.e., universities of applied sciences, as well as *Pädagogische Hochschulen*, i.e., teacher training colleges, and other institutions of tertiary education in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Pforzheim University is one of the oldest Fachhochschulen in Germany which is renowned and highly ranked for its engineering and MBA programs.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The state has the highest density of universities of any state in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Railways form a major part of the transport infrastructure in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] As of 2017, the main standard gauge railway network managed by DB InfraGO consists of about 3,350 kilometres (2,080 mi) of railway lines connecting all major settlements of the state, with about 6,500 trains operating every day.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] As part of high-speed rail in Germany, the Mannheim–Stuttgart and Stuttgart–Ulm high-speed lines were built, and the Karlsruhe–Basel high-speed line, paralleling the traditional Mannheim–Karlsruhe–Basel railway, is currently under construction.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In and around Stuttgart, the old terminal station is currently being replaced with an underground through station as part of the controversial Stuttgart 21 project.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Passenger train services in Baden-Württemberg are operated partly by various subsidiaries of Deutsche Bahn, the national railway operator, such as DB Fernverkehr with its high-speed ICE, as well as IC trains; and DB Regio, operating some regional train services in the state.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Cross-border train services are also provided by French Railways' TGV trains, as well as by Swiss Federal Railways and Austrian Federal Railways (including its Nightjet night trains).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Since the 1990s, the around 120 individual regional train services in Baden-Württemberg have been managed by the state-owned Nahverkehrsgesellschaft Baden-Württemberg (NVBW), which has started to commercially tender out these train operations.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] DB Regio, SWEG, HzL, AVG and WEG have been joined in operating regional trains by Agilis, Bodensee-Oberschwaben-Bahn, Arverio, SBB, Schwäbische Alb-Bahn and VIAS, which entered the market.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Starting in the 1970s, regional rail around major cities has been transformed into high-frequent S-Bahn networks, currently the following systems exist (partly) in Baden-Württemberg: Stuttgart S-Bahn, Rhine-Neckar S-Bahn, Breisgau S-Bahn and Basel S-Bahn.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In and around the cities of Karlsruhe and Heilbronn, the Karlsruhe Stadtbahn system combines elements of traditional S-Bahns with tram operations within the urban cores (tram-trains).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In Württemberg, the Royal State Railways opened their first line on 22 October 1845 between two present-day suburbs of Stuttgart.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In 1900, the Hohenzollerische Landesbahn (HzL) was founded to expand the rail system in the Prussian province, which had previously only been served by short sections of Württemberg lines passing through "foreign" territory.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] After the construction of the main lines, various private or local government initiatives constructed branch or local railway lines, some of which survive today as AVG, SWEG, RNV or WEG lines.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In 1920, the Baden and Württemberg state railways merged with other state railways to form Deutsche Reichsbahn, which was replaced by Deutsche Bundesbahn after World War II.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] A lot of smaller railway lines, both DB and remaining local or private lines, closed in the decades after World War II, or were at least run-down with minimal service for passengers.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Since the 1990s, some of these lines have been revived and revitalised marking good examples for increased ridership through attractive trains and timetables, with some examples being the Kraichgau Railway (taken over by AVG) and the Schönbuch Railway (reopened by WEG).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] A popular TV programme portraying railways around Germany and the world, *Eisenbahn-Romantik*, originates in Baden-Württemberg and is produced by its public broadcaster SWR.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg's area is covered by 19 *Verkehrsverbünde* (transport associations), organising and managing local public transport, as well as ensuring harmonised fares between different bus and train operators.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] For inter-*Verbünde* journeys, the *bwtarif*, created in 2018, offers seamless tickets across the state.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] As of 2023, tram and light rail systems exist in Freiburg, Heidelberg, Heilbronn, Karlsruhe, Mannheim, Stuttgart and Ulm.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] International tram lines also reach Baden-Württemberg: Basel's tram 8 serves Weil am Rhein, while Strasbourg's tram D extends to Kehl.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] There is also a trolleybus system in Esslingen am Neckar.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg is served by several airports.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The largest is Stuttgart Airport, which functions as the state’s main international hub.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Other commercial airports include Karlsruhe/Baden-Baden Airport and Friedrichshafen Airport.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The EuroAirport Basel Mulhouse Freiburg, located on the French–German–Swiss border, Frankfurt Airport and Zurich Airport are also frequently used by passengers from the region.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In 2006, the birth rate of 8.61 per 1000 was almost equal to the death rate of 8.60 per 1000.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] 14.87 percent of the population was under the age of 15, whereas the proportion of people aged 65 and older was at 18.99 per cent (2008).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The dependency ratio–the ratio of people aged under 15 and over 64 in comparison to the working-age population (aged 15–64)–was 512 per 1000 (2008).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In 2018, Baden-Württemberg ranked 2 on the Human Development Index (HDI) among all states in Germany, after Hamburg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] With an average life expectancy of 79.8 years for men and 84.2 years for women (2017–2019 life table), Baden-Württemberg ranks first in this category among all states in Germany for both sexes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg has long been a preferred destination of immigrants.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] As of 2013, almost 28% of its population had a migration background as defined by the Federal Statistical Office of Germany; this number clearly surpassed the German average of 21% and was higher than in any other German state with the exception of the city states of Hamburg and Bremen.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] As of 2014, 9,355,239 of the population held German citizenship, whereas 1,131,421 were foreign nationals.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Northern and most of central Württemberg has been traditionally Protestant (particularly Lutheran) since the Reformation in 1534 (with its centre at the famous Tübinger Stift).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The former Electorate of the Palatinate (Northwestern Baden) with its capital Heidelberg was shaped by Calvinism before being integrated into Baden.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Upper Swabia, and the Upper Neckar Valley up to the bishop seat of Rottenburg, and Southern Baden (the Catholic archbishop has its seat in Freiburg) have traditionally been bastions of Roman Catholicism.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Catholics have a very narrow plurality in the state, with 6% of the population adhering to Islam and 24% of the population disclaiming any religion or adhering to other faiths.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Football is the biggest sport in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Clubs currently competing in the Bundesliga include SC Freiburg, TSG 1899 Hoffenheim and the most successful club in the state, VfB Stuttgart, meanwhile Karlsruher SC, 1.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] FC Heidenheim, SV Sandhausen and Waldhof Mannheim also compete in the top three German soccer divisions.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Handball-Bundesliga multiple champions Frisch Auf Göppingen and Rhein-Neckar Löwen, as well as TVB 1898 Stuttgart are based in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Frisch Auf Göppingen won EHF Champions League (Europe's premier club tournament) twice, in 1960 and 1962.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Several major women's handball clubs are also based here, including 3-time Frauen Bundesliga champions SG BBM Bietigheim.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Compared to other German states, Baden-Württemberg has a particularly high density of professional basketball teams such as Riesen Ludwigsburg, ratiopharm Ulm, USC Heidelberg, PS Karlsruhe Lions and others.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] One of the most decorated German ice hockey clubs, Adler Mannheim, is based in the city of Mannheim.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Other DEL clubs, such as Bietigheim Steelers and Schwenninger Wild Wings are also based in the state.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Baden-Württemberg is home to the most successful club in German volleyball history, the Volleyball-Bundesliga club VfB Friedrichshafen, which won CEV Champions League in 2006–07 season.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] There are also multiple motorsport facilities, the most famous one being long-time Formula One circuit Hockenheimring.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Alemannic and Franconian dialects of German are spoken in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Slightly different variants of the Alemannic dialect Swabian are spoken in central and southern Württemberg, including in Upper Swabia, the Swabian Alb, and the central Neckar Valley of the Stuttgart region.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In South Baden, the local dialects are Low Alemannic and High Alemannic (i.e., variants of what is also Swiss German).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In the northern part of Baden, i.e., the area around Karlsruhe, Heilbronn and Mosbach, South Franconian dialects are predominant.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In the *Kurpfalz*, however, with the cities of Heidelberg and Mannheim, the idiom is Rhine Franconian (i.e., Palatinate German), while in the Northeast of Baden-Württemberg East Franconian is spoken.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] The same or similar Alemannic dialects are also spoken in the neighboring regions, especially in Bavarian Swabia, Alsace (Alsatian), German-speaking Switzerland (Swiss German), and the Austrian Vorarlberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] In contrast, the other Franconian dialects range from the Netherlands over the Rhineland, Lorraine, and Hesse up to Franconia in northern Bavaria.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] Yiddish and Pleißne were spoken while Romani is still being used by some.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/baden-württemberg] A variant of the Alemannic German of Baden developed into the Colonia Tovar dialect, spoken by descendants of immigrants from Baden who went to Venezuela in 1843.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Palmer's controversial and polarizing positions put forward with great self-conviction led to the withdrawal of support from his party in the 2020 municipal elections, and a process to oust him from party ranks was started the following year.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Palmer was born in Waiblingen, Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] His father, Helmut, dubbed *Remstalrebell* ("Rems-valley rebel") was a very well known and controversial figure and perennial candidate.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] The former state minister and CDU member Christoph Palmer is a second nephew of Helmut and a second cousin of Boris Palmer.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Palmer graduated from high school (*Abitur*) at the Steiner School in Winterbach-Engelberg in 1992.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] From 1993, Palmer studied history and mathematics at the University of Tübingen and in Sydney.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] After graduating from Tübingen in 1999 Palmer worked as a scientific assistant for the Green Party in the Bundestag, the German Federal parliament, in Berlin.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] In March 2001 he won a seat in the Landtag of Baden-Württemberg and was appointed party spokesman for environmental and transportation issues.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] In 2004 he ran for the office of mayor of Stuttgart, finishing in third place in the first round ballot at 21.5% of votes, a better result than all previous Green candidates for mayor of Stuttgart.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Even though that has been the case, Schuster has not kept that promise.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] After being re-elected to the Landtag in March 2006, Palmer decided in July to run as mayor of Tübingen and won the election on 22 October with 50.4% of the vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] He subsequently resigned from his Landtag mandate after taking office in January 2007.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] In July 2009, Palmer was criticized for recommending antizionist activist and Tübingen resident Felicia Langer for the Federal Cross of Merit.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Palmer was a Green Party delegate to the Federal Convention for the purpose of electing the president of Germany in 2010.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] In March 2011, the Greens won the Baden-Württemberg state election: after decades, the CDU lost its power.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Since then, Minister-President of Baden-Württemberg is a Greens politician, Winfried Kretschmann.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] In November 2012, after Palmer had been critical of child adoption by homosexual couples and criticism about him being not much of a team player, the central Green party council did not reelect him.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] On 19 October 2014, Palmer was reelected for another eight-year term.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Palmer's relatively conservative stance within the Greens is well known and he has been deemed as controversial in the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] His use of Facebook, e.g. with regard to a landlord that was not willing to serve drinks on inn's terrace, has caused some conflicts and doubts about his diplomatic skills.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] As a result of repeated accusations of racism against Boris Palmer, the Green Party of Baden-Württemberg initiated party order proceedings against him at a digital party conference on 8 May 2021 with the aim of expelling him.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] On 15 November 2021, the state executive of the Green Party of Baden-Württemberg officially applied for Palmer's expulsion from the party.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] After being dismissed from the Green Party, Boris Palmer ran the 2022 Tübingen Mayor Election as an independent candidate.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] He won the election with a clear majority by securing 52 % of votes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Palmer apparently wants to run for the Free Voters party in the local elections in 2024.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] In December 2023, the party confirmed talks with Palmer, who wanted to become active at the local level for the Free Voters faction in the district council Kreistag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Palmer initiated a project for a light rail through the old town of Tübingen.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] He declared it the main part of his policy for a different traffic policy ("Verkehrswende").
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] The municipal council and the university also backed the project.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] However, in a referendum, 57.39 percent of Tübingen citizens voted against the inner-city route in summer 2021.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] In late 2015, Palmer was heavily criticized by other members of the Green Party, as well as by the party's youth organization, for his relatively right-wing positions on refugee immigration.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] In August 2017, some weeks before the German federal election, Palmer published the book "We cannot help everyone" (German: *Wir können nicht allen helfen*, lit.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] On 5 May 2020, *The New York Times* reported that "Boris Palmer, the mayor of Tübingen, in the country's southwest, suggested that reviving the economy mattered more than the lives of potential coronavirus victims, whom he characterized as old and unwell.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Palmer's candidacy in 2022 is based, among other things, on a survey in Tübingen, according to which the citizens want him back as mayor.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] The survey was carried out among 500 people from Tübingen in October 2021, shortly after the federal elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] Various topics were queried in it, the question about Palmer was only one.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/boris-palmer] In February 2022, Palmer admitted to DLF that he had commissioned and paid for the survey at the time.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The **Bundestag** (German: [ˈbʊndəstaːk] ⓘ, 'Federal Diet') is the federal parliament of Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] It is the only constitutional body in the country directly elected by the German people.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag was established by Title III of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany (*Grundgesetz*) in 1949 as one of the legislative bodies of Germany, the other being the Bundesrat.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The members of the Bundestag are representatives of the German people as a whole, are not bound by any orders or instructions and are only accountable to their conscience.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Since the current 21st legislative period, the Bundestag has a fixed number of 630 members.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected every four years by German citizens aged 18 and older.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Elections use a mixed-member proportional representation system which combines first-past-the-post voting for constituency-seats with proportional representation to ensure its composition mirrors the national popular vote.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The German Bundestag cannot dissolve itself; only the president of Germany can do so under certain conditions.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of government at the federal level.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag is considerably more powerful than the Bundesrat, which represents the state governments.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] All bills must first be passed in the Bundestag before they are discussed in the Bundesrat.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundesrat can only accept laws passed by the Bundestag without amendment.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Only in some areas, where laws directly affect the states, can the Bundesrat reject laws; otherwise, it can only lodge an objection to them, which the Bundestag can overrule.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Above all, however, the chancellor and the federal government are solely responsible to the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag also has sole budgetary authority.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Since 1999, the Bundestag has met in the Reichstag building in Berlin.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag also operates in multiple new government buildings in Berlin around the neo-renaissance house and has its own police force (the *Bundestagspolizei*), directly subordinated to the Bundestag Presidency.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag's presiding officer is the president of the Bundestag; they are deputized by the Vice Presidents of the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Since 2025, Julia Klöckner of the CDU/CSU is the president of the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In the protocol order of the federation, the President of the Bundestag ranks second after the President and before the Chancellor.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The first body to be called Bundestag was the legislative body of the German Confederation, which convened in Frankfurt am Main from 1816 to 1866.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] This Bundestag was a convention of state envoys.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] During the revolution of 1848/49, the National Assembly, which met in Frankfurt am Main, was the first elected German parliament and served as a constituent assembly for a German state, which ultimately did not come to pass.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The North German Confederation, founded in 1866/67, was the first German nation state with an established elected parliament, however this ended up being called the Reichstag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In 1870/71, the federation was expanded to include the southern German territories and was henceforth called the German Empire.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Reichstag building, where the current Bundestag meets since 1999 (see below), was built in 1888.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The German Empire was not yet a parliamentary democracy in the modern sense, but a constitutional monarchy with democratic elements.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Reichstag had to approve all bills, had the right to initiate legislation and, in particular, had budgetary sovereignty.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] However, the Chancellor and the imperial government were not responsible to parliament, but to the emperor alone.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] It was not until 1918, a few weeks before the end of the First World War, that the Reichstag was given the right, as part of a constitutional reform, to withdraw its confidence in the Chancellor and thus force him to resign.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] There was also no universal suffrage for the Reichstag; only men over the age of 25 were entitled to vote in Reichstag elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] After its defeat in the First World War, Germany became a republic and a parliamentary democracy with the Weimar Constitution of 1919.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The voting age was lowered to 21 years and women were given the right to vote for (and serve in) the Reichstag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] However, the first German democracy failed for various reasons, some of which were directly related to the Reichstag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The pure proportional representation system in elections did not produce clear majorities and the various parties were not sufficiently willing to compromise to form stable governments.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] This led to numerous changes of government and snap elections.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In the last years of the Weimar Republic, opposition parties on the far-right and the far-left held the majority of seats in the Reichstag, which led the governments to rule largely by emergency decrees and bypass parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In 1933, Adolf Hitler was appointed chancellor and through the Reichstag Fire Decree, the Enabling Act of 1933 and the death of President Paul von Hindenburg in 1934, gained unlimited power.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] After this, the Reichstag, in which only the Nazi Party was represented from November 1933 on, met only rarely, above all to extend the emergency laws on which the Nazi dictatorship was formally based.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] With the Basic Law of 1949, Germany's second democratic constitution, the Bundestag was established as the new parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Due to the division of Germany, the Bundestag was de facto a West German parliament until 1990.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The socialist GDR in East Germany had its own parliament, the Volkskammer, which, however, did not emerge from democratic elections except for its last electoral term in 1990.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Because West Berlin was not officially under the jurisdiction of the Basic Law during the division, the Bundestag met in Bonn in several different buildings, including (provisionally) a former waterworks facility and finally in the Bundeshaus.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In addition, owing to the city's legal status, citizens of West Berlin were unable to vote in elections to the Bundestag, and were instead represented by 22 non-voting delegates chosen by the House of Representatives, the city's legislature.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Since German reunification in 1990, the Bundestag has once again been an all-German parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In 1999, the German parliament moved from Bonn to Berlin and sits once again in the Reichstag building.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of the German political system.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag is one of three constitutional bodies (along with the Bundesrat and the federal government) that have the right of initiative for the legislative process.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In order to introduce a bill in the Bundestag, the support of a faction or of a number of MPs corresponding to at least 5% of all MPs is required.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] All bills (including those introduced by the Bundesrat and the government) are first voted on in the Bundestag (for bills from the Bundesrat and the government, however, an opinion must first be obtained from the other body).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] A bill is first discussed at first reading, then referred to one or more committees, where it can be amended; the resulting committee version then goes back to the plenary, where it is passed at second and third reading.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Amendments can also be tabled at this stage.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] A simple majority (more yes votes than no votes with no regard to abstentions) is required for normal legislative proposals.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In some very rare cases, the Basic Law requires the so-called chancellor majority (majority of all members of parliament) for simple laws, for example to establish new intermediate and subordinate federal authorities.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Laws amending the Basic Law require a two-thirds majority of all members of the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] A law passed by the Bundestag is passed on to the Bundesrat.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Amendments to the Basic Law and laws that directly affect the states must be passed by the Bundesrat by majority vote (amendments to the Basic Law, again, by a two-thirds majority); all other laws are considered passed if the Bundesrat does not object to them within 14 days.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In no case can the Bundesrat make amendments to a bill.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] If the Bundesrat rejects a bill, the matter is often referred to the so-called mediation committee, a body made up of an equal number of members of the Bundestag and Bundesrat, which attempts to negotiate whether the bill can find the approval of both chambers with certain amendments.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] A version amended in this way must then be passed again by a majority in both chambers in order to become law (in this case the rules of procedure of both chambers provide for an abbreviated legislative procedure).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In the final step, a law must be signed by the President of Germany (they have a right of veto in theory, but this has been used very rarely in the history of the Federal Republic).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag has an elective function for a number of offices.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The chancellor is elected by the Bundestag and formally appointed by the president of Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] A chancellor's election is necessary whenever the office of chancellor has fallen vacant.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] This is the case if a newly elected Bundestag meets for the first time, or during legislative periods, if the former chancellor died or resigned.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The chancellor's election is one of the few cases in which a vote in the Bundestag requires a majority of all elected members, not just a majority of those assembled at the time, the so-called *Kanzlermehrheit* ("chancellor majority").
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] As with other elections performed by the Bundestag, the chancellor is elected via secret ballot.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] If the nominee reaches the necessary "chancellor majority", the president appoints him or her and, after that, the president of the Bundestag will administer the oath of office before the assembled house.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] If this nominee is not elected, the right of nomination is transferred onto the Bundestag: Candidates can now be nominated for election, whereby a nomination must be supported by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag can hold any number of ballots in this manner for two weeks.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] To be elected, a candidate still needs a "chancellor majority" of yes-votes ("Second voting phase").
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] If the Bundestag is unable to elect a chancellor in these fourteen days, a final ballot is held on the very next day.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Once again, candidates can be nominated by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Candidates receiving a "chancellor majority" in this ballot are elected.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Otherwise, it is up to the President of Germany either to appoint the candidate with the plurality of votes as Chancellor or to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections ("Third voting phase").
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Another possibility to vote a new chancellor into office is the constructive vote of no confidence, which allows the Bundestag to replace a sitting chancellor, if it elects a new chancellor with the "chancellor-majority".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag shares responsibility with the Bundesrat for electing the judges of the Federal Constitutional Court.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Both chambers elect four judges to each of the court's two senates.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] They also elect the president and vice-president of the Federal Constitutional Court in alternating order.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In the Bundestag, this requires a two-thirds majority of members present, which has equal at least a majority of all members.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The majority ratios in the Bundestag therefore do not necessarily have to correspond to those in the Federal Assembly.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected for four years, and new elections must be held no earlier than 46 and no later than 48 months after the beginning of a given legislative term.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] By way of exception, there may be an early election if the President of Germany dissolves the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] However, the President only has the right to do so in the event of a failed chancellor election or if an incumbent chancellor requests dissolution after losing a vote of confidence.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The possibility of an early election is therefore in theory much more limited than is the case in some other parliamentary democracies.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] This restriction is intended to encourage the parliamentary groups to cooperate in difficult situations, and is a lesson learned from the experience of the Weimar Republic, in which snap elections were very frequent because the parties were unable to compromise and form stable governments.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] A legislative term ends at the moment when a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for the first time, which must occur within 30 days after an election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The principle applies that there can be no "period without parliament".
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] An elected Bundestag is fully competent to act until a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for its first session.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Prorogations and dissolutions (in the strict sense), as known in the Westminster system, do not exist in Germany.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Even an early dissolution of the Bundestag, as described above, in practice only leads to an early election, but does not end the legislative period itself.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Following the tradition of German parliamentarism, the Bundestag is subject to the *principle of discontinuation*, meaning that a newly-elected Bundestag is legally regarded as a body and entity completely different from the previous Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] This leads to the result that any motion, application or action submitted to the previous Bundestag, e.g. a bill referred to the Bundestag by the Federal Government, is regarded as void by non-decision (German terminology: "*Die Sache fällt der Diskontinuität anheim*").
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Thus any bill that has not been decided upon by the beginning of the new electoral period must be brought up by the government again if it aims to uphold the motion, this procedure in effect delaying the passage of the bill.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Furthermore, any newly-elected Bundestag will have to freshly decide on the rules of procedure (*Geschäftsordnung*), which is done by a formal decision of taking over such rules from the preceding Bundestag by reference.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] If the succeeding Bundestag convenes with same or similar majorities like its predecessor, the parliament can decide to take over earlier initiatives of legislation in the same fashion to abbreviate the process, thus effectively breaking the principle of discontinuation by a pull.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Before an electoral reform in 2023, the Bundestag nominally had 598 members, with the mixture of majority and proportional representation regularly leading to a large number of additional overhang and compensation mandates.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Every elector has two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a party list vote (second vote).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The second votes are used to produce proportionality with respect to the total number of 630 seats; first at the federal level and then at state level (using the Sainte-Laguë method).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In most cases, the number of constituencies won by a party in a given state does not exactly correspond to the number of seats to which the party is entitled in that state via second votes.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] To qualify for any seats, however, a party must either win three single-member constituencies via first votes (basic mandate clause) or exceed a threshold of 5% of the second votes nationwide.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] This does not apply to independent constituency candidates: these always enter the Bundestag if they win their constituency.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] (However, no independent constituency candidate has won a constituency since 1949).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Seats allocated in this way are subtracted from the base number of 630 when the mandates are distributed among the parties.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In addition, the second votes of voters who have elected a successful independent candidate in a constituency are not taken into account when calculating the number of mandates (although they are for the 5% threshold).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Parties representing recognized national minorities (currently Danes, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people) are exempt from both the 5% national threshold and the basic mandate clause.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The only party that has been able to benefit from this provision so far at the federal level is the South Schleswig Voters' Association, which represents the minorities of Danes and Frisians in Schleswig-Holstein, and succeeded in winning a seat in 1949, 2021, and 2025.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] If a member of parliament leaves the Bundestag during the current legislative term, either through resignation or death, another candidate from that party from the corresponding state takes their place.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Successful constituency candidates who did not receive a seat in the previous election due to the principle of second vote coverage are considered first, followed by the candidates on the respective state list.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] However, if the list is exhausted, the seat in question remains vacant for the remainder of the term.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] If the departing member was an independent constituency candidate, the seat also remains empty.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The latest federal election was held on Sunday, 23 February 2025, to elect the members of the 21st Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The executive bodies of the Bundestag are the Presidium and the Council of Elders.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Presidium consists of the President, the presiding officer, and several Vice Presidents.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The President and Vice Presidents are elected by the plenary of the Bundestag, whereby traditionally the largest fraction nominates the President and each fraction may nominate a vice president.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In addition to the members of the Presidium, the Council of Elders includes 23 other deputies who are delegated proportionally by the factions.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The council is the coordination hub, determining the daily legislative agenda and assigning committee chairpersons based on Parliamentary group representation.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The council also serves as an important forum for interparty negotiations on specific legislation and procedural issues.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Presidium is responsible for the routine administration of the Bundestag, including its clerical and research activities.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag cannot be adjourned or prorogued during the current legislative term, but is always fully capable of acting and sets its own legislative calendar.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Normally, the Bundestag sits for at least twenty weeks per year, interrupted by non-sessional weeks, especially a long parliamentary summer recess, during which the MPs are present in their constituencies.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The course of a session week is traditionally always the same: meetings of the parliamentary faction's internal committees take place on Monday and Tuesday mornings, and meetings in the faction-plenary on Tuesday afternoon.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] From Wednesday to Friday, plenary sessions and committee meetings take place in parallel (this is the reason why often very few members are present at plenary debates).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Committee meetings are interrupted on very important items on the agenda so that all MPs have the opportunity to be present in the plenary hall.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The highlights of the procedures include government statements by the Chancellor and the general debate at the beginning of the annual budget deliberations, during which there is a direct clash between the Chancellor and the opposition leader.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Independently of the usual procedure, the Bundestag can also convene for extraordinary sessions at any time.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] This must happen if one third of the MPs, the President of Germany or the Chancellor request it (Basic Law, Article 39.3).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The most important organisational structures within the Bundestag are 'factions' (*Fraktionen*; sing.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] A parliamentary faction must consist of at least 5% of all members of parliament.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Members of parliament from different parties may only join in a faction if those parties did not run against each other in any German state during the election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Normally, all parties that surpassed the 5%-threshold build a faction of their own.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The CDU and CSU however, have always formed a joint faction, called CDU/CSU or Union.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] This is possible, as the CSU only runs in the state of Bavaria and the CDU only runs in the other 15 states.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The size of a faction determines the extent of its representation on committees, the time slots allotted for speaking, the number of committee chairs it can hold, and its representation in executive bodies of the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The factions, not the members, receive the bulk of government funding for legislative and administrative activities.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The leadership of each *Fraktion* consists of a parliamentary party leader, several deputy leaders, and an executive committee.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The leadership's major responsibilities are to represent the *Fraktion*, enforce party discipline and orchestrate the party's parliamentary activities.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The members of each *Fraktion* are distributed among working groups focused on specific policy-related topics such as social policy, economics, and foreign policy.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The *Fraktion* meets every Tuesday afternoon in the weeks in which the Bundestag is in session to consider legislation before the Bundestag and formulate the party's position on it.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Parties that do not hold 5% of the Bundestag-seats may be granted the status of a *group* in the Bundestag; this is decided case by case, as the rules of procedure do not state a fixed number of seats for this.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] This status entails some privileges which are in general less than those of a faction.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Most of the legislative work in the Bundestag is the product of standing committees, which exist largely unchanged throughout one legislative period.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The number of committees approximates the number of federal ministries, and the titles of each are roughly similar (e.g., defense, agriculture, and labor).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] There are, as of the current nineteenth Bundestag, 24 standing committees.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The distribution of committee chairs and the membership of each committee reflect the relative strength of the various Parliamentary groups in the chamber.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] In the current nineteenth Bundestag, the CDU/CSU chaired ten committees, the SPD five, the AfD and the FDP three each, The Left and the Greens two each.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Members of the opposition party can chair a significant number of standing committees (e.g. the Budget Committee of the Bundestag was by tradition chaired by the biggest opposition party, until the 21st Bundestag, when Alternative for Germany was denied this post).
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] These committees have either a small staff or no staff at all.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The members of Bundestag and the presidium are supported by the Bundestag Administration.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] It is headed by the Director, that reports to the President of the Bundestag.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag Administrations four departments are Parliament Service, Research, Information / Documentation and Central Affairs.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag Administration employs around 3,000 employees.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Also following the tradition of German diets, the German Bundestag can legally convene on any location, domestic and foreign.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Reichstag plenary chamber is not determined by law as the location of the assembly, making it a facility of convenience.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Bundestag's predecessor, the German Reichstag, convened in the Kroll Opera House in Berlin, after the Reichstag with its then wooden interior and walls burned down in the Reichstag fire.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] After World War II, the Bundestag did not have own facilities to call home and had to convene in the Bundeshaus in Bonn together with the Bundesrat.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] 1953, the plenary chambers in the Bundeshaus had to be expanded and the Bundestag assembled in a radio building in Cologne.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Until 1965, the Bundestag assembled in West Berlin for nine sessions.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Seven sessions have been held in the Technische Universität Berlin and two sessions in Berlin's Congress Hall in Tiergarten.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The assemblies met severe protest from the communist side, the last session even interrupted by Soviet aircraft in supersonic low-altitude flight.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] 1971, the four occupying powers agreed to not accept Bundestag assemblies in West Berlin anymore.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled in the Old Waterworks Building in Bonn when the old plenary chamber had to get broken down, and in the new plenary chamber for only a few years after Germany's reunification.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The most distinctive assembly of the Bundestag outside its regular chambers was on 4 October 1990, the day after German reunification.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled inside the Reichstag building in Berlin for the first time after 57 years, and remote from its then-regular home in Bonn.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/bundestag] Soon after this most memorable assembly, the Bundestag decided to move from Bonn back to Berlin by a law which sets only the city of Berlin to be the home of the Bundestag, not the building.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] They have developed in parallel in the 1940s, act on federal level as "the Union" CDU/CSU, but have never merged.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] CDU is the major party of the centre-right in German politics.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Friedrich Merz has been federal chairman of the CDU since 31 January 2022, and has served as the Chancellor of Germany since 6 May 2025.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU/CSU is the largest faction in the 21st Bundestag, the current German federal legislature, with 208 (164 CDU + 44 CSU) out of 630 seats, having won a combined 28.5% (22.6% CDU and 6.0% CSU) of votes in the 2025 federal election.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The group's parliamentary leader has been Jens Spahn since 5 May 2025.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Founded in 1945 as an interdenominational Christian party, the CDU effectively succeeded the traditional Catholic Centre Party that was active from 1870 until 1933.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] When political parties were allowed in Allied-occupied Germany, many former Centre members joined the all-Christian CDU, including its first leader Konrad Adenauer.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The party also included politicians of other backgrounds, including liberals and conservatives.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] As a result, the party claims to represent "Christian-social, liberal and conservative" elements.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU is generally pro-European in outlook.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Black, associated with Christian clerical robes like cassock/soutane, is the party's customary and historical electoral color, used in many polls and other publications.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Since the change in the CDU corporate design in 2023, the font of their logo was changed from red to black.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The logo is on a white frame and always connected with the Flag of Germany black-red-gold *upswing*.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Two of the others preferred CDU colors are named after places where Konrad Adenauer had lived, Cadenabbia-Turquoise, dark Rhöndorf-Blue, plus White and Union-Gold.
[src:2018-freiburg-gang-rape/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU leads the federal government in a grand coalition with the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD), after returning as the largest party in the 2025 federal election.
